ing film directors]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Musicians from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:People from Carmel-by-the-Sea, California]]\n[[Category:People from Pebble Beach, California]]\n[[Category:People from Piedmont, California]]\n[[Category:Producers who won the Best Picture Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Rising Sun, 3rd class]]\n[[Category:Screen Actors Guild Life Achievement Award]]\n[[Category:Seattle University alumni]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States National Medal of Arts recipients]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) film directors]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) television actors]]\n[[Category:People from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "name_user": "AAHale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2000s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clint_Eastwood"}
{"title_page": "Work permit", "text_new": "{{short description|Document permitting holder to work}}\n{{about|the visa|the work safety management system|Permit To Work}}\n\nA '''work permit''' or '''work visa''' is the permission to take a [[job]] within a foreign country.\n\n== European Union ==\n{{see also|Blue Card (European Union)}}\nCurrently, every EU country has a different process for granting work permits to nationals of non-EU countries. To address this issue, the European Commission began work in 1999 on developing an EU-wide process for the entry of non-EU nationals into the work force.<ref name=\"Towards a Common European Union Immigration Policy\">{{cite web |url=http://ec.europa.eu/justice_home/fsj/immigration/fsj_immigration_intro_en.htm |title=Towards a Common European Union Immigration Policy |accessdate=2007-03-03 |publisher=European Commission}}</ref>  In October 2007, they adopted a proposal to introduce a work permit similar to the United States' \"Green Card\" program, called the \"Blue Card\". It is similar to the UK's [[Highly Skilled Migrant Programme]], with the exception that it will require an employment contract in place prior to migration.  After two years in the first country, the migrant will be allowed to move and work in another EU country, and can sum the number of years spent in the EU for purposes of residency. This new card will abolish work permits across the EU and centralize the issuing from Brussels.\n<ref name=\"EU Blue Card to encourage highly-qualified non-EU citizens to work in the EU\">{{cite web |url=http://ec.europa.eu/ireland/press_office/news_of_the_day/bluecard_en.htm |title=EU Blue Card to encourage highly-qualified non-EU citizens to work in the EU |accessdate=2007-03-03 |publisher=European Commission, Irish Press Office }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n{{main article|Work permit (Belgium)}}\n\n===Czech Republic===\nThe issuing of work permit in the Czech Republic is governed by three basic sources: labor code, Act No. 435/2004 Coll. On employment and Act no. 326/1999 Coll. On the residence of foreign nationals. There are various rights and obligations depending on nationality.<ref>https://ppropo.mpsv.cz/zakon_435_2004</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visaworkers.cz/news/types-of-visa-in-the-czech-republic|title=Visa Workers - Types of visa in the Czech Republic|website=Visa Workers.cz}}</ref>\n\n===France===\nThe procedure to get a work permit is quite elaborate since the applicant should prove that no French jobseeker fitted the position.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alain-Christian |last=Monkam|title=How to get a work permit in France|website= Village de la Justice|year= 2011|url= http://www.village-justice.com/articles/permit-France,11079.html}}</ref>{{pov-inline|date=June 2019}}\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{main article|Work permit (United Kingdom)}}\nThere are seven standard ways to apply for a work permit in the United Kingdom: the Business and Commercial Arrangements, the Training and Work Experience Arrangements, the Sports people and Entertainers Arrangements, Student Internships, GATS, Ancestry Visa and the Sectors Based Scheme. All applications require the work permit holder to leave the country where the work permit was issued every three months under the Work Permit Arrangements. Costs for leaving the airport are \u00a364, per person and you must return to the airport after 24 hours or one working day to leave the country. If you remain in the airport the cost is \u00a335 per person and you must leave the country after 24 hours or one working day in the airport.  <ref name=\"Working in the UK - Work Permit Arrangements\">{{cite web |url=http://www.workingintheuk.gov.uk/working_in_the_uk/en/homepage/work_permits0/applying_for_a_work.html |title=Working in the UK - Work Permit Arrangements |accessdate=2007-03-03 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom}}</ref> Each of these involves its own application process, and generally requires a job offer from a UK employer.\n\nUK Work visas allow for extended visa options which may lead to permanent residence. With Europe at its doorstep and a large domestic market, the various UK work visa categories offer a gateway for thousands of applicants seeking the experience of European life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.migrationexpert.co.uk/work_visa/|title= UK Work Visa - Visa Service & Advice Online|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe UK work permit system is currently being replaced by a new [[Points-based immigration system (United Kingdom)|points-based immigration system]].\n\n==Russia==\nAccording to the Federal Migration Service of Russia estimates, in Russia today there are 5 million working foreign nationals.\n\nIn order to work in Russia, foreign citizens must have a work visa (visa for arriving at the order) to obtain a work permit and get on migration registration in the Russian Federal Migration Service bodies.\n\nFor foreign citizens arriving without visas ([[CIS countries]] except [[Turkmenistan]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) there is a simplified procedure. The period of temporary stay for them is 90 days, but can be extended up to one year from the date of entry into the Russian Federation on presentation of the migration service of the employment contract or a contract of civil-legal nature. That is, a foreigner can obtain a work permit for up to 90 days, and then to extend it after the job. However, it is recommended to immediately impose a labor or civil contract and to issue a work permit for the duration of its validity.\n\nIssuance of work permits is carried out taking into account the established quota. The quota is divided by region, Russia and the integrated vocational qualification groups.\n\nA work permit is divided to some categories:\n*Qualified professionals are employed by their existing profession (specialty), included in the approved list of professions (specialties, positions);\n*Highly qualified professionals engaged in labor activity in accordance with the provisions of Article 13 of the Federal Law \"On the Legal Status of Foreign Citizens in the Russian Federation.\"\nThe work permit is valid within the subject of the Russian Federation, in which it was issued.\n\n== Ukraine ==\nForeigners and [[Statelessness|stateless]] persons can be employed in [[Ukraine]] after obtaining an appropriate permit. These requirements are established by article 42 of the Law of Ukraine \"On Employment\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.clc.co.ua/work-permit-in-ukraine/|title=Work permit in Ukraine. Obtaining and legislation.|last=Thor|first=Anatoliy}}</ref> State Employment Service of Ukraine is the main authority to issue work permit. \n\nDoes not require obtaining a work permit for:\n* foreigners who have [[Permanent residency|residence permit]] in Ukraine;\n* [[Refugee|refugees]];\n* foreigners who have permission to immigrate to Ukraine;\n* foreigners who are recognized as persons in need of additional protection, or who are granted temporary protection in Ukraine;\n* representatives of foreign maritime (river) fleet and airlines that serve such companies on the territory of Ukraine;\n* employees of foreign media who are accredited to work in Ukraine;\n* professional athletes, artists and art workers to work in Ukraine;\n* workers of emergency services for urgent work;\n* employees of foreign representative (branch) office that are registered in the territory of Ukraine in accordance with the procedure established by the law;\n* ecclesiastic who are to reside in Ukraine temporarily (on the ground of invitation of religious organization) for canonical activity only in such religious organization;\n* foreigners who arrived in Ukraine to participate in the implementation of international technical assistance projects;\n* foreigners who arrived in Ukraine to conduct teaching and / or scientific activities in higher education institutions;\n* other foreigners in cases provided by laws and international treaties of Ukraine;\n* Obtaining work permit in Ukraine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.clc.co.ua/work-permit-in-ukraine/|title=Work permit in Ukraine. Legal services and advisory - Law Firm \"Capital Law Consulting\"|publisher=}}</ref> is one of the basics to obtain residence permit.\n\n== United States ==\n[[File:Getting_working_papers._New_York._-_NARA_-_523068.jpg|thumb|Applying for working papers, 1908 ([[United States Children's Bureau]])]]\nIn general, the United States does not require work permits for adult [[Citizenship in the United States|citizen]]s. However, certain aliens are required to have an [[Employment Authorization Document]] from the [[United States Citizenship and Immigration Services]] (USCIS) of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS).\n\nThe [[federal government of the United States]] does not require work permits or proof-of-age certificates for a minor to be employed.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\">{{cite web | title= Youth & Labor: Work Permits & Age Certificates | url= http://www.dol.gov/dol/topic/youthlabor/workpermitsagecert.htm}}</ref> However, the possession of an age certificate constitutes a good faith effort to comply with minimum age requirements of the [[Fair Labor Standards Act]] of 1938.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\"/> The [[United States Department of Labor]] will issue a \"certificate of age\" if the minor employee's state does not issue them, or if the minor is requested by his or her employer to provide one.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\"/><ref>{{USCFR|29|570}}</ref> Several states are not listed in {{USCFR|29|570|9}}(a), such as Alaska, Arizona, Idaho, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, Texas, and Utah, and thus their certificates may not meet the requirements of {{USCFR|29|570|5}}(b) as being evidence of compliance with the Fair Labor Standards Act.\n\nMany states also require them for workers of certain ages.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\"/> In some states, for example [[New Jersey]], permits are only required for minors 14 and 15 years old, while others such as [[Massachusetts]] require, at least in theory, work permits for all minors until they turn 18 years of age. In some states, enforcement is strict. Permits are usually issued through the school system the minor attends, and typically at a minimum is conditioned on enrollment in high school with regular attendance (no chronic absenteeism, tardiness, or truancy). Some states such as [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[Indiana]] require high school students with part-time jobs to maintain a certain [[grade point average]]. Minors who are working are usually restricted in the number of hours each day or week they are permitted to work as well as the types of jobs they may hold.\n\n== Turkey ==\n\nThe immigration in Turkey is regulated by the {{ill|General Directorate of Immigration Management|tr|G\u00f6\u00e7 \u0130daresi Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goc.gov.tr/main/Eng_3|title=Ministry Of Interior Directorate General Of Migration Management|website=www.goc.gov.tr}}</ref> (G\u00f6\u00e7 \u0130daresi Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc) under the supervision of the [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Ministry of Interior]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mia.gov.tr/|title=Ministry of Interior - Republic of Turkey|website=www.mia.gov.tr}}</ref> while work permits are delivered by the {{ill|General Directorate of Labor Immigration|tr|Uluslararas\u0131 \u0130\u015fg\u00fcc\u00fc Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc}} (Uluslararas\u0131 \u0130\u015fg\u00fcc\u00fc Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc) under the supervision of the [[Ministry of Labour and Social Security (Turkey)|Ministry of Labour and Social Security]] (T\u00fcrkiye Cumhuriyeti \u00c7al\u0131\u015fma ve Sosyal G\u00fcvenlik Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csgb.gov.tr/En|title=T.C. \u00c7ALI\u015eMA VE SOSYAL G\u00dcVENL\u0130K BAKANLI\u011eI - Anasayfa|first=T.C. \u00c7al\u0131\u015fma ve Sosyal G\u00fcvenlik Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131 - Bilgi \u0130\u015flem Daire Ba\u015fkanl\u0131\u011f\u0131, \u0130nternet Hizmetleri \u015eubesi|last=M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|website=www.csgb.gov.tr|access-date=2016-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029043402/http://www.csgb.gov.tr/En|archive-date=2016-10-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> All applications for both residence permit and work permit are made through online government portals. The residence permit application is made through \"  \"e-Residence\" (e-\u0130kamet)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e-ikamet.goc.gov.tr/|title=Directorate General of Migration Management|website=e-ikamet.goc.gov.tr}}</ref> while {{ill|Turkish work permit|tr|T\u00fcrkiye'de \u00e7al\u0131\u015fma izni}} application are made through [[e-Government (Turkey)]] (e-Devlet).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.turkiye.gov.tr/|title=e-Devlet Kap\u0131s\u0131 Devletin K\u0131sayolu - www.t\u00fcrkiye.gov.tr|website=www.turkiye.gov.tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://residencepermitturkey.com/foreigners-convert-to-turkish-id-and-passport-in-turkey/|title=Foreigners convert to Turkish ID and Passport in Turkey/|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==South Africa==\nThere are three categories of South African work visa or permit available to a foreigner each with its own set of specific requirements all assisting in immigration to South Africa or working in South Africa. These are the ''General Work Visa/Permit'', the ''Critical Skills Work Visa/Permit'' and the ''Intra-Company Transfer Work Visa/Permit''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Work Permits in South Africa |url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/work-permit-south-africa/ |accessdate=2015-07-08 |publisher=Immigration South Africa\u2122}}</ref> Due to recent immigration law changes (May, 2014), the obtaining of work visas or permits in South Africa has become much more arduous. Furthermore, these work permits are now referred to as visas.\n\n'''General Work Visa/Permit''' - \nThe basis of a general work visa/permit is that a firm offer of employment has been made by a prospective employer to a foreigner after such employer has unsuccessfully exploited the local labour market in attempting to procure the needed skills, experiences or qualifications equivalent of such foreigner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/general-work-visa-south-africa/|title=General Work Visa - Immigration South Africa\u2122|website=www.immigrationsouthafrica.org}}</ref>\n\n'''Critical Skills Work Visa/Permit''' - \nA critical skills work permit may be issued to a foreigner who possesses critical skills or qualifications and is able to demonstrate with supporting documentation in the form of testimonials, publications. This is based on a list published by the Department of Home Affairs in South Africa called the Critical Skills List <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/Critical_Skills_Work_Visa_List.pdf|title=South Africa's latest Critical Skills List (PDF)|publisher=}}</ref> A letter of motivation from an authoritative body to substantiate the benefits that those skills will bring to South Africa. This critical skills work permit is granted for up to five years and may be renewed for a further period, if required.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/critical-skills/|title=Critical Skills Work Visa - Immigration South Africa\u2122|website=www.immigrationsouthafrica.org}}</ref> This visa type replaces the previously issued Quota Work Permit and the Exceptional Skills Work Permit.\n\n'''Intra-Company Transfer Work Visa/Permit'''  - \nAn intra company transfer work permit is issued to a foreigner who is normally deployed or seconded to South African branch, subsidiary or associate office of a corporate entity aboard.\nThere are strict controls to ensure that the foreigner remains employed in his or her specific position during the tour of duty. This type of visa is only valid for two years, and often no extension is possible. Also, any applicant must have first worked for a minimum of 6 months in the employ of the company\u2019s foreign office before applying to relocate and immigrate to the South African branch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/work-permit-south-africa/|title=Work Visas for South Africa - Immigration South Africa\u2122|website=www.immigrationsouthafrica.org}}</ref>\n\n==Canada==\nCanada work permits are issued under the Temporary Foreign Worker Program (TFWP) by Canada immigration and Citizenship.\n\nThe TFWP has four streams: high-skilled workers, low-skilled workers, the Seasonal Agricultural Worker Program, and the Live-In Caregiver Program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Singer|first1=Colin|title=Canada Work Permit|url=http://www.immigration.ca/canada-work-visa/|website=immigration.ca|date=2013-04-27}}</ref>\n\n==Philippines==\nIn the Philippines, legal employment of a foreigner in the country for a period of more than six months requires an alien employment permit (AEP) which is issued by the Department of Labor and Employment. A special working permit (SWP) issued by the Bureau of Immigration is required instead for foreigners intending to work in the country for a period of less than six months.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Medenilla |first1=Samuel |title=Rising number of foreign workers shows job-skills mismatch persisting in PHL |url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2018/03/27/rising-number-of-foreign-workers-shows-job-skills-mismatch-persisting-in-phl/ |accessdate=5 September 2019 |work=BusinessMirror |date=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Singapore==\nIn [[Singapore]], the [[Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)|Ministry of Manpower]] (MOM) issues work passes to eligible foreigners in accordance to the Employment of Foreign Manpower Act (EFMA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Employment of Foreign Manpower Act |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/legislation/employment-of-foreign-manpower-act |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref>\n\nThere are three main categories of work passes:<ref>{{cite web |title=Work passes and permits |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref>\n*Work Permit (WP) - for unskilled and semi-skilled workers. Subject to quota{{ref|quota|a}} and levy{{ref|levy|b}} requirements. Not allowed to bring family members to Singapore. Not eligible to apply for [[Permanent residency in Singapore|permanent residence]]. Marriage restrictions apply; current or former WP holders must seek approval from MOM before marrying a Singapore citizen or permanent resident.\n:Subsets of Work Permit include Work Permit for foreign [[domestic worker]], Work Permit for [[postpartum confinement|confinement]] nanny and Work Permit for performing artiste working in public entertainment outlets.\n*S Pass (SP) - for mid-level skilled staff and technicians earning a fixed monthly salary of at least [[Singapore dollar|S$]]2,300. Subject to quota and levy requirements. Allowed to bring family members to Singapore if earning a fixed monthly salary of at least S$6,000. Eligible to apply for permanent residence.\n*Employment Pass (EP) - for professionals, managers and executives earning a fixed monthly salary of at least S$3,600. Not subject to quota and levy requirements, but fair consideration must be given to qualified local jobseekers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fair Consideration Framework |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/employment-practices/fair-consideration-framework |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref> Allowed to bring family members to Singapore if earning a fixed monthly salary of at least S$6,000. Eligible to apply for permanent residence.\n:A special type of EP is the Personalised Employment Pass (PEP). An EP holder can apply for a PEP if he/she earns a fixed monthly salary of at least S$12,000. For foreign executives relocating to Singapore and applying for a PEP, their last drawn fixed monthly salary must be at least S$18,000. The PEP is not tied to a particular employer, and the PEP holder can spend up to six months unemployed in Singapore. The PEP is valid for up to 3 years and non-renewable.<ref>{{cite web |title=Key facts on Personalised Employment Pass |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits/personalised-employment-pass/key-facts |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Eligibility and requirements for Personalised Employment Pass |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits/personalised-employment-pass/eligibility-and-requirements |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref>\n\nOther types of work passes include EntrePass (allowing entrepreneurs to set up businesses in Singapore), Work Holiday Pass (for eligible foreign students to work and holiday in Singapore), Training Employment Pass (short-term training for professionals) and Training Work Permit (short-term training for semi-skilled trainees).\n\nNotes:\n:{{note|quota|a}} a number of locals (Singapore citizens or permanent residents) must be employed by the employer before a foreign worker can be hired\n:{{note|levy|b}} a daily or monthly tax on each foreign worker, borne by the employer\n\n==Australia==\nSeveral different types of visas are available for immigrants. {{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Thailand ==\nForeigners holding a \"B\" visa and wishing to work or start a business in Thailand are required to obtain a work permit. The issuance of work permits is under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Labor of Thailand. Work without permission in the Kingdom is criminally punishable. It takes 7 working days to process the application for a permit. If the applicant is qualified and able to use \"One Stop Service Center\", the work permit will only take one day.\n\n=== Duties ===\n'''Thai government fees for a work permit:'''\n*100 Baht/form = Permit application Fee.\n*750 Baht = work permit not longer than 3 months.\n*1,500 Baht = work permit longer than 3 months but does not exceed 6 months.\n*3,000 Baht = work permit longer than 6 months but does not exceed 12 months.\n'''Thai government fees for amendments:'''\n*500 Baht/Book = Substitute of a permit.\n*1,000 Baht/time = Permission to change or add job description.\n*3,000 Baht/time = Permission to remove or add an employer.\n*1,000 Baht/time = Permission to change or add the locality or place of work.\n*150 Baht/time = Permission to change or add conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gam-legalalliance.com/services/immigration/thai-visas/thai-work-permit/work-permit-fees-in-thailand/|title=Work Permit Fees in Thailand {{!}} G.A.M. Legal Alliance|publisher=gam-legalalliance.com|lang=en|accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\nAccording to the Emergency Decree on Non-Thais' Working Management No. 2, 2018, foreigners can work anywhere in the country without having to record these changes in the permit, but each employer must be listed in the book. If the employee is transferred to another office in another part of the country, the employer should notify the office of the Employment Department.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Phuket News: New Work Permit rules confirmed by Phuket Employment Office Chief|first=The Phuket News|last=Com|url=https://www.thephuketnews.com/new-work-permit-rules-confirmed-by-phuket-employment-office-chief-68463.php#hKPzXuOSWSyAwLX3.97|work=The Phuket News Com|accessdate=2018-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Professions that are prohibited for foreigners ===\nThe Thai Ministry of Labor has developed a list of professions that foreigners are prohibited from working in the Kingdom. This is done so that the local population does not suffer from unemployment due to the influx of immigrants.<br>\n'''List of prohibited professions:'''\n#Labour work except labour work in fishing boats under the next category below. The said work which is forbidden to aliens shall not apply to aliens who have entered into Thailand under an agreement on hire of labour concluded between the Government of Thailand and other nations, and also aliens whose status has been prescribed as legal immigrant and who possess a residence certificate under the law governing immigration.\n#Agriculture, animal husbandry, forestry or fishery, except work requiring specialized knowledge, farm supervision, or labour work in fishing boats, particularly marine fishery.\n#Bricklaying, carpentry, or other construction work.\n#Wood carving.\n#Driving motor vehicles or vehicles which do not use machinery or mechanical devices, except piloting aircraft internationally.\n#Front shop sales and auction sale work.\n#Supervising, auditing, or giving service in accountancy, except occasional internal auditing.\n#Cutting or polishing precious or semi-precious stones.\n#Haircutting, hairdressing, or beautification.\n#Cloth weaving by hand.\n#Mat weaving or making utensils from reed, rattan, jute, hay, or bamboo.\n#Making rice paper by hand.\n#Lacquer work.\n#Making Thai musical instruments.\n#Niello work.\n#Goldsmith, silversmith, or gold/copper alloy smith work.\n#Stone work.\n#Making Thai dolls.\n#Making mattresses or quilts.\n#Making alms bowls.\n#Making silk products by hand.\n#Making Buddha images.\n#Knifemaking.\n#Making paper or cloth umbrellas.\n#Making shoes.\n#Making hats.\n#Brokerage or agency except in international trading.\n#Professional civil engineering concerning design and calculation, systemization, analysis, planning, testing, construction supervision, or consulting services, excluding work requiring specialized techniques.\n#Professional architectural work concerning design, drawing/making, cost estimation, or consulting services.\n#Dressmaking.\n#Pottery.\n#Cigarette rolling by hand.\n#Tour guiding or conducting.\n#Hawking of goods & Thai typesetting by hand.\n#Unwinding and twisting silk by hand.\n#Clerical or secretarial work.\n#Providing legal services or engaging in legal work, except arbitration work; and work relating to defense of cases at arbitration level, provided the law governing the dispute under consideration by the arbitrators is not Thai law, or it is a case where there is no need to apply for the enforcement of such arbitration award in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thailawonline.com/en/others/labour-law/forbidden-occupations-for-foreigners-jobs.html|title=Forbidden Occupations for Foreigners (Jobs) - thailawonline|publisher=thailawonline.com|lang=en-GB|accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Expatriate]]\n* [[Stamp 4]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n<!-- Please check http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:External_links before posting links here -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Work Permit}}\n[[Category:Labour law]]\n[[Category:Legal documents]]\n[[Category:Immigration law]]\n[[Category:Employment of foreign-born]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Document permitting holder to work}}\n{{about|the visa|the work safety management system|Permit To Work}}\n\nA '''work permit''' or '''work visa''' is the permission to take a [[job]] within a foreign country.\n\n== European Union ==\n{{see also|Blue Card (European Union)}}\nCurrently, every EU country has a different process for granting work permits to nationals of non-EU countries. To address this issue, the European Commission began work in 1999 on developing an EU-wide process for the entry of non-EU nationals into the work force.<ref name=\"Towards a Common European Union Immigration Policy\">{{cite web |url=http://ec.europa.eu/justice_home/fsj/immigration/fsj_immigration_intro_en.htm |title=Towards a Common European Union Immigration Policy |accessdate=2007-03-03 |publisher=European Commission}}</ref>  In October 2007, they adopted a proposal to introduce a work permit similar to the United States' \"Green Card\" program, called the \"Blue Card\". It is similar to the UK's [[Highly Skilled Migrant Programme]], with the exception that it will require an employment contract in place prior to migration.  After two years in the first country, the migrant will be allowed to move and work in another EU country, and can sum the number of years spent in the EU for purposes of residency. This new card will abolish work permits across the EU and centralize the issuing from Brussels.\n<ref name=\"EU Blue Card to encourage highly-qualified non-EU citizens to work in the EU\">{{cite web |url=http://ec.europa.eu/ireland/press_office/news_of_the_day/bluecard_en.htm |title=EU Blue Card to encourage highly-qualified non-EU citizens to work in the EU |accessdate=2007-03-03 |publisher=European Commission, Irish Press Office }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n{{main article|Work permit (Belgium)}}\n\n===Czech Republic===\nThe issuing of work permit in the Czech Republic is governed by three basic sources: labor code, Act No. 435/2004 Coll. On employment and Act no. 326/1999 Coll. On the residence of foreign nationals. There are various rights and obligations depending on nationality.<ref>https://ppropo.mpsv.cz/zakon_435_2004</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visaworkers.cz/news/types-of-visa-in-the-czech-republic|title=Visa Workers - Types of visa in the Czech Republic|website=Visa Workers.cz}}</ref>\n\n===France===\nThe procedure to get a work permit is quite elaborate since the applicant should prove that no French jobseeker fitted the position.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alain-Christian |last=Monkam|title=How to get a work permit in France|website= Village de la Justice|year= 2011|url= http://www.village-justice.com/articles/permit-France,11079.html}}</ref>{{pov-inline|date=June 2019}}\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{main article|Work permit (United Kingdom)}}\nThere are seven standard ways to apply for a work permit in the United Kingdom: the Business and Commercial Arrangements, the Training and Work Experience Arrangements, the Sports people and Entertainers Arrangements, Student Internships, GATS, Ancestry Visa and the Sectors Based Scheme. All applications require the work permit holder to leave the country where the work permit was issued every three months under the Work Permit Arrangements. Costs for leaving the airport are \u00a364, per person and you must return to the airport after 24 hours or one working day to leave the country. If you remain in the airport the cost is \u00a335 per person and you must leave the country after 24 hours or one working day in the airport.  <ref name=\"Working in the UK - Work Permit Arrangements\">{{cite web |url=http://www.workingintheuk.gov.uk/working_in_the_uk/en/homepage/work_permits0/applying_for_a_work.html |title=Working in the UK - Work Permit Arrangements |accessdate=2007-03-03 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom}}</ref> Each of these involves its own application process, and generally requires a job offer from a UK employer.\n\nUK Work visas allow for extended visa options which may lead to permanent residence. With Europe at its doorstep and a large domestic market, the various UK work visa categories offer a gateway for thousands of applicants seeking the experience of European life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.migrationexpert.co.uk/work_visa/|title= UK Work Visa - Visa Service & Advice Online|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe UK work permit system is currently being replaced by a new [[Points-based immigration system (United Kingdom)|points-based immigration system]].\n\n==Russia==\nAccording to the Federal Migration Service of Russia estimates, in Russia today there are 5 million working foreign nationals.\n\nIn order to work in Russia, foreign citizens must have a work visa (visa for arriving at the order) to obtain a work permit and get on migration registration in the Russian Federal Migration Service bodies.\n\nFor foreign citizens arriving without visas ([[CIS countries]] except [[Turkmenistan]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) there is a simplified procedure. The period of temporary stay for them is 90 days, but can be extended up to one year from the date of entry into the Russian Federation on presentation of the migration service of the employment contract or a contract of civil-legal nature. That is, a foreigner can obtain a work permit for up to 90 days, and then to extend it after the job. However, it is recommended to immediately impose a labor or civil contract and to issue a work permit for the duration of its validity.\n\nIssuance of work permits is carried out taking into account the established quota. The quota is divided by region, Russia and the integrated vocational qualification groups.\n\nA work permit is divided to some categories:\n*Qualified professionals are employed by their existing profession (specialty), included in the approved list of professions (specialties, positions);\n*Highly qualified professionals engaged in labor activity in accordance with the provisions of Article 13 of the Federal Law \"On the Legal Status of Foreign Citizens in the Russian Federation.\"\nThe work permit is valid within the subject of the Russian Federation, in which it was issued.\n\n== Ukraine ==\nForeigners and [[Statelessness|stateless]] persons can be employed in [[Ukraine]] after obtaining an appropriate permit. These requirements are established by article 42 of the Law of Ukraine \"On Employment\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.clc.co.ua/work-permit-in-ukraine/|title=Work permit in Ukraine. Obtaining and legislation.|last=Thor|first=Anatoliy}}</ref> State Employment Service of Ukraine is the main authority to issue work permit. \n\nDoes not require obtaining a work permit for:\n* foreigners who have [[Permanent residency|residence permit]] in Ukraine;\n* [[Refugee|refugees]];\n* foreigners who have permission to immigrate to Ukraine;\n* foreigners who are recognized as persons in need of additional protection, or who are granted temporary protection in Ukraine;\n* representatives of foreign maritime (river) fleet and airlines that serve such companies on the territory of Ukraine;\n* employees of foreign media who are accredited to work in Ukraine;\n* professional athletes, artists and art workers to work in Ukraine;\n* workers of emergency services for urgent work;\n* employees of foreign representative (branch) office that are registered in the territory of Ukraine in accordance with the procedure established by the law;\n* ecclesiastic who are to reside in Ukraine temporarily (on the ground of invitation of religious organization) for canonical activity only in such religious organization;\n* foreigners who arrived in Ukraine to participate in the implementation of international technical assistance projects;\n* foreigners who arrived in Ukraine to conduct teaching and / or scientific activities in higher education institutions;\n* other foreigners in cases provided by laws and international treaties of Ukraine;\n* Obtaining work permit in Ukraine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.clc.co.ua/work-permit-in-ukraine/|title=Work permit in Ukraine. Legal services and advisory - Law Firm \"Capital Law Consulting\"|publisher=}}</ref> is one of the basics to obtain residence permit.\n\n== United States ==\n[[File:Getting_working_papers._New_York._-_NARA_-_523068.jpg|thumb|Applying for working papers, 1908 ([[United States Children's Bureau]])]]\nIn general, the United States does not require work permits for adult [[Citizenship in the United States|citizen]]s. However, certain aliens are required to have an [[Employment Authorization Document]] from the [[United States Citizenship and Immigration Services]] (USCIS) of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS).\n\nThe [[federal government of the United States]] does not require work permits or proof-of-age certificates for a minor to be employed.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\">{{cite web | title= Youth & Labor: Work Permits & Age Certificates | url= http://www.dol.gov/dol/topic/youthlabor/workpermitsagecert.htm}}</ref> However, the possession of an age certificate constitutes a good faith effort to comply with minimum age requirements of the [[Fair Labor Standards Act]] of 1938.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\"/> The [[United States Department of Labor]] will issue a \"certificate of age\" if the minor employee's state does not issue them, or if the minor is requested by his or her employer to provide one.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\"/><ref>{{USCFR|29|570}}</ref> Several states are not listed in {{USCFR|29|570|9}}(a), such as Alaska, Arizona, Idaho, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, Texas, and Utah, and thus their certificates may not meet the requirements of {{USCFR|29|570|5}}(b) as being evidence of compliance with the Fair Labor Standards Act.\n\nMany states also require them for workers of certain ages.<ref name=\"dol_youth_certs\"/> In some states, for example [[New Jersey]], permits are only required for minors 14 and 15 years old, while others such as [[Massachusetts]] require, at least in theory, work permits for all minors until they turn 18 years of age. In some states, enforcement is strict. Permits are usually issued through the school system the minor attends, and typically at a minimum is conditioned on enrollment in high school with regular attendance (no chronic absenteeism, tardiness, or truancy). Some states such as [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[Indiana]] require high school students with part-time jobs to maintain a certain [[grade point average]]. Minors who are working are usually restricted in the number of hours each day or week they are permitted to work as well as the types of jobs they may hold.\n\n== Turkey ==\n\nThe immigration in Turkey is regulated by the {{ill|General Directorate of Immigration Management|tr|G\u00f6\u00e7 \u0130daresi Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goc.gov.tr/main/Eng_3|title=Ministry Of Interior Directorate General Of Migration Management|website=www.goc.gov.tr}}</ref> (G\u00f6\u00e7 \u0130daresi Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc) under the supervision of the [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Ministry of Interior]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mia.gov.tr/|title=Ministry of Interior - Republic of Turkey|website=www.mia.gov.tr}}</ref> while work permits are delivered by the {{ill|General Directorate of Labor Immigration|tr|Uluslararas\u0131 \u0130\u015fg\u00fcc\u00fc Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc}} (Uluslararas\u0131 \u0130\u015fg\u00fcc\u00fc Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc) under the supervision of the [[Ministry of Labour and Social Security (Turkey)|Ministry of Labour and Social Security]] (T\u00fcrkiye Cumhuriyeti \u00c7al\u0131\u015fma ve Sosyal G\u00fcvenlik Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csgb.gov.tr/En|title=T.C. \u00c7ALI\u015eMA VE SOSYAL G\u00dcVENL\u0130K BAKANLI\u011eI - Anasayfa|first=T.C. \u00c7al\u0131\u015fma ve Sosyal G\u00fcvenlik Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131 - Bilgi \u0130\u015flem Daire Ba\u015fkanl\u0131\u011f\u0131, \u0130nternet Hizmetleri \u015eubesi|last=M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|website=www.csgb.gov.tr|access-date=2016-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029043402/http://www.csgb.gov.tr/En|archive-date=2016-10-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> All applications for both residence permit and work permit are made through online government portals. The residence permit application is made through \"  \"e-Residence\" (e-\u0130kamet)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e-ikamet.goc.gov.tr/|title=Directorate General of Migration Management|website=e-ikamet.goc.gov.tr}}</ref> while {{ill|Turkish work permit|tr|T\u00fcrkiye'de \u00e7al\u0131\u015fma izni}} application are made through [[e-Government (Turkey)]] (e-Devlet).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.turkiye.gov.tr/|title=e-Devlet Kap\u0131s\u0131 Devletin K\u0131sayolu - www.t\u00fcrkiye.gov.tr|website=www.turkiye.gov.tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expatguideturkey.com/acquisition-of-turkish-citizenship-i/|title=CITIZENSHIP IN TURKEY|newspaper=Expat Guide Turkey|language=tr-TR|access-date=2016-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==South Africa==\nThere are three categories of South African work visa or permit available to a foreigner each with its own set of specific requirements all assisting in immigration to South Africa or working in South Africa. These are the ''General Work Visa/Permit'', the ''Critical Skills Work Visa/Permit'' and the ''Intra-Company Transfer Work Visa/Permit''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Work Permits in South Africa |url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/work-permit-south-africa/ |accessdate=2015-07-08 |publisher=Immigration South Africa\u2122}}</ref> Due to recent immigration law changes (May, 2014), the obtaining of work visas or permits in South Africa has become much more arduous. Furthermore, these work permits are now referred to as visas.\n\n'''General Work Visa/Permit''' - \nThe basis of a general work visa/permit is that a firm offer of employment has been made by a prospective employer to a foreigner after such employer has unsuccessfully exploited the local labour market in attempting to procure the needed skills, experiences or qualifications equivalent of such foreigner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/general-work-visa-south-africa/|title=General Work Visa - Immigration South Africa\u2122|website=www.immigrationsouthafrica.org}}</ref>\n\n'''Critical Skills Work Visa/Permit''' - \nA critical skills work permit may be issued to a foreigner who possesses critical skills or qualifications and is able to demonstrate with supporting documentation in the form of testimonials, publications. This is based on a list published by the Department of Home Affairs in South Africa called the Critical Skills List <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/Critical_Skills_Work_Visa_List.pdf|title=South Africa's latest Critical Skills List (PDF)|publisher=}}</ref> A letter of motivation from an authoritative body to substantiate the benefits that those skills will bring to South Africa. This critical skills work permit is granted for up to five years and may be renewed for a further period, if required.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/critical-skills/|title=Critical Skills Work Visa - Immigration South Africa\u2122|website=www.immigrationsouthafrica.org}}</ref> This visa type replaces the previously issued Quota Work Permit and the Exceptional Skills Work Permit.\n\n'''Intra-Company Transfer Work Visa/Permit'''  - \nAn intra company transfer work permit is issued to a foreigner who is normally deployed or seconded to South African branch, subsidiary or associate office of a corporate entity aboard.\nThere are strict controls to ensure that the foreigner remains employed in his or her specific position during the tour of duty. This type of visa is only valid for two years, and often no extension is possible. Also, any applicant must have first worked for a minimum of 6 months in the employ of the company\u2019s foreign office before applying to relocate and immigrate to the South African branch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationsouthafrica.org/work-permit-south-africa/|title=Work Visas for South Africa - Immigration South Africa\u2122|website=www.immigrationsouthafrica.org}}</ref>\n\n==Canada==\nCanada work permits are issued under the Temporary Foreign Worker Program (TFWP) by Canada immigration and Citizenship.\n\nThe TFWP has four streams: high-skilled workers, low-skilled workers, the Seasonal Agricultural Worker Program, and the Live-In Caregiver Program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Singer|first1=Colin|title=Canada Work Permit|url=http://www.immigration.ca/canada-work-visa/|website=immigration.ca|date=2013-04-27}}</ref>\n\n==Philippines==\nIn the Philippines, legal employment of a foreigner in the country for a period of more than six months requires an alien employment permit (AEP) which is issued by the Department of Labor and Employment. A special working permit (SWP) issued by the Bureau of Immigration is required instead for foreigners intending to work in the country for a period of less than six months.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Medenilla |first1=Samuel |title=Rising number of foreign workers shows job-skills mismatch persisting in PHL |url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2018/03/27/rising-number-of-foreign-workers-shows-job-skills-mismatch-persisting-in-phl/ |accessdate=5 September 2019 |work=BusinessMirror |date=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Singapore==\nIn [[Singapore]], the [[Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)|Ministry of Manpower]] (MOM) issues work passes to eligible foreigners in accordance to the Employment of Foreign Manpower Act (EFMA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Employment of Foreign Manpower Act |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/legislation/employment-of-foreign-manpower-act |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref>\n\nThere are three main categories of work passes:<ref>{{cite web |title=Work passes and permits |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref>\n*Work Permit (WP) - for unskilled and semi-skilled workers. Subject to quota{{ref|quota|a}} and levy{{ref|levy|b}} requirements. Not allowed to bring family members to Singapore. Not eligible to apply for [[Permanent residency in Singapore|permanent residence]]. Marriage restrictions apply; current or former WP holders must seek approval from MOM before marrying a Singapore citizen or permanent resident.\n:Subsets of Work Permit include Work Permit for foreign [[domestic worker]], Work Permit for [[postpartum confinement|confinement]] nanny and Work Permit for performing artiste working in public entertainment outlets.\n*S Pass (SP) - for mid-level skilled staff and technicians earning a fixed monthly salary of at least [[Singapore dollar|S$]]2,300. Subject to quota and levy requirements. Allowed to bring family members to Singapore if earning a fixed monthly salary of at least S$6,000. Eligible to apply for permanent residence.\n*Employment Pass (EP) - for professionals, managers and executives earning a fixed monthly salary of at least S$3,600. Not subject to quota and levy requirements, but fair consideration must be given to qualified local jobseekers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fair Consideration Framework |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/employment-practices/fair-consideration-framework |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref> Allowed to bring family members to Singapore if earning a fixed monthly salary of at least S$6,000. Eligible to apply for permanent residence.\n:A special type of EP is the Personalised Employment Pass (PEP). An EP holder can apply for a PEP if he/she earns a fixed monthly salary of at least S$12,000. For foreign executives relocating to Singapore and applying for a PEP, their last drawn fixed monthly salary must be at least S$18,000. The PEP is not tied to a particular employer, and the PEP holder can spend up to six months unemployed in Singapore. The PEP is valid for up to 3 years and non-renewable.<ref>{{cite web |title=Key facts on Personalised Employment Pass |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits/personalised-employment-pass/key-facts |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Eligibility and requirements for Personalised Employment Pass |url=https://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits/personalised-employment-pass/eligibility-and-requirements |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)}}</ref>\n\nOther types of work passes include EntrePass (allowing entrepreneurs to set up businesses in Singapore), Work Holiday Pass (for eligible foreign students to work and holiday in Singapore), Training Employment Pass (short-term training for professionals) and Training Work Permit (short-term training for semi-skilled trainees).\n\nNotes:\n:{{note|quota|a}} a number of locals (Singapore citizens or permanent residents) must be employed by the employer before a foreign worker can be hired\n:{{note|levy|b}} a daily or monthly tax on each foreign worker, borne by the employer\n\n==Australia==\nSeveral different types of visas are available for immigrants. {{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Thailand ==\nForeigners holding a \"B\" visa and wishing to work or start a business in Thailand are required to obtain a work permit. The issuance of work permits is under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Labor of Thailand. Work without permission in the Kingdom is criminally punishable. It takes 7 working days to process the application for a permit. If the applicant is qualified and able to use \"One Stop Service Center\", the work permit will only take one day.\n\n=== Duties ===\n'''Thai government fees for a work permit:'''\n*100 Baht/form = Permit application Fee.\n*750 Baht = work permit not longer than 3 months.\n*1,500 Baht = work permit longer than 3 months but does not exceed 6 months.\n*3,000 Baht = work permit longer than 6 months but does not exceed 12 months.\n'''Thai government fees for amendments:'''\n*500 Baht/Book = Substitute of a permit.\n*1,000 Baht/time = Permission to change or add job description.\n*3,000 Baht/time = Permission to remove or add an employer.\n*1,000 Baht/time = Permission to change or add the locality or place of work.\n*150 Baht/time = Permission to change or add conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gam-legalalliance.com/services/immigration/thai-visas/thai-work-permit/work-permit-fees-in-thailand/|title=Work Permit Fees in Thailand {{!}} G.A.M. Legal Alliance|publisher=gam-legalalliance.com|lang=en|accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\nAccording to the Emergency Decree on Non-Thais' Working Management No. 2, 2018, foreigners can work anywhere in the country without having to record these changes in the permit, but each employer must be listed in the book. If the employee is transferred to another office in another part of the country, the employer should notify the office of the Employment Department.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Phuket News: New Work Permit rules confirmed by Phuket Employment Office Chief|first=The Phuket News|last=Com|url=https://www.thephuketnews.com/new-work-permit-rules-confirmed-by-phuket-employment-office-chief-68463.php#hKPzXuOSWSyAwLX3.97|work=The Phuket News Com|accessdate=2018-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Professions that are prohibited for foreigners ===\nThe Thai Ministry of Labor has developed a list of professions that foreigners are prohibited from working in the Kingdom. This is done so that the local population does not suffer from unemployment due to the influx of immigrants.<br>\n'''List of prohibited professions:'''\n#Labour work except labour work in fishing boats under the next category below. The said work which is forbidden to aliens shall not apply to aliens who have entered into Thailand under an agreement on hire of labour concluded between the Government of Thailand and other nations, and also aliens whose status has been prescribed as legal immigrant and who possess a residence certificate under the law governing immigration.\n#Agriculture, animal husbandry, forestry or fishery, except work requiring specialized knowledge, farm supervision, or labour work in fishing boats, particularly marine fishery.\n#Bricklaying, carpentry, or other construction work.\n#Wood carving.\n#Driving motor vehicles or vehicles which do not use machinery or mechanical devices, except piloting aircraft internationally.\n#Front shop sales and auction sale work.\n#Supervising, auditing, or giving service in accountancy, except occasional internal auditing.\n#Cutting or polishing precious or semi-precious stones.\n#Haircutting, hairdressing, or beautification.\n#Cloth weaving by hand.\n#Mat weaving or making utensils from reed, rattan, jute, hay, or bamboo.\n#Making rice paper by hand.\n#Lacquer work.\n#Making Thai musical instruments.\n#Niello work.\n#Goldsmith, silversmith, or gold/copper alloy smith work.\n#Stone work.\n#Making Thai dolls.\n#Making mattresses or quilts.\n#Making alms bowls.\n#Making silk products by hand.\n#Making Buddha images.\n#Knifemaking.\n#Making paper or cloth umbrellas.\n#Making shoes.\n#Making hats.\n#Brokerage or agency except in international trading.\n#Professional civil engineering concerning design and calculation, systemization, analysis, planning, testing, construction supervision, or consulting services, excluding work requiring specialized techniques.\n#Professional architectural work concerning design, drawing/making, cost estimation, or consulting services.\n#Dressmaking.\n#Pottery.\n#Cigarette rolling by hand.\n#Tour guiding or conducting.\n#Hawking of goods & Thai typesetting by hand.\n#Unwinding and twisting silk by hand.\n#Clerical or secretarial work.\n#Providing legal services or engaging in legal work, except arbitration work; and work relating to defense of cases at arbitration level, provided the law governing the dispute under consideration by the arbitrators is not Thai law, or it is a case where there is no need to apply for the enforcement of such arbitration award in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thailawonline.com/en/others/labour-law/forbidden-occupations-for-foreigners-jobs.html|title=Forbidden Occupations for Foreigners (Jobs) - thailawonline|publisher=thailawonline.com|lang=en-GB|accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Expatriate]]\n* [[Stamp 4]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n<!-- Please check http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:External_links before posting links here -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Work Permit}}\n[[Category:Labour law]]\n[[Category:Legal documents]]\n[[Category:Immigration law]]\n[[Category:Employment of foreign-born]]\n", "name_user": "176.43.196.247", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eTurkey)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Work_permit"}
{"title_page": "The Doon School Weekly", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper |\nname = The Doon School Weekly |\nimage = The Doon School Weekly.jpg |\ntype = [[Weekly newspaper|Weekly]] [[student newspaper]] |\nowners = [[The Doon School]]|\nformat = [[Compact (newspaper)|Compact]] |\nfoundation = 1936 by [[Arthur Foot]]|\npolitical = None|\nlanguage = English|\npublisher  =Indian Public Schools' Society| \nheadquarters = Publications Room, Arts and Media Centre<br>[[The Doon School]]<br>[[Dehradun]]-248001<br>India |\ncirculation = c. 600 |\noclc = 224047237 |\nwebsite = http://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/\n}}\n\n'''''The Doon School Weekly''''' (informally '''''Weekly''''') is a [[student newspaper]] produced by and for the students of [[The Doon School]].<ref>https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon</ref> It was established in 1936, a year after the school's founding, by the first headmaster [[Arthur Foot]]. The ''Weekly'' is the oldest and flagship publication of the school, and the newspaper's constitution grants it [[editorial independence]].<ref name=>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |last=Futehally |first=Laeeq |date=24 February 2002 |website=The Hindu |access-date=1 March 2012}}</ref> The paper, distributed every Saturday morning, carries a mix of reports on school activities, trips or expeditions, opinion pieces, critique of school policies, interviews of visiting speakers, student polls, crossword, cartoons, and creative writing, including short stories, poetry, satire or personal essays. The alumni keep up to date with the developments at school through the newspaper, which is also published online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2015/state-editions/a-beloved-teacher-of-the-doon-school.html|title=A beloved teacher of the Doon School|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref>  Notable alumni in the fields of literature, journalism, politics and academia have been former editors of the publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/from-doon-school-to-jnanpith-award--amitav-ghosh---s-amazing-journey.html|title=From Doon School to Jnanpith Award: Amitav Ghosh\u2019s amazing journey|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/features/nature-cricket-literature-history-1502519395.html|title=Of nature, cricket, literature and history|date=29 October 2017}}</ref> The Weekly's sister publications at the school are ''Infinity'', ''The Doon School Information Review'', ''The Circle'', and ''The Yearbook''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimonen|first=Eija|title=Education and Society in Comparative Context|year=2015|publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]|location=|isbn=9789463003735|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=SmM-CwAAQBAJ&|page=143|quote=In addition to producing a conventional yearbook, the students also produced other periodicals, such as the school's special publications: ''The Doon School Information Review''...and the scientific bi-annual ''The Echo'' and ''Cosmos''.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFounded by Arthu Foot in 1936, ''The Doon School Weekly'' is owned by Indian Public Schools' Society, the governing society of [[The Doon School]]. For the first three years of its existence, the newspaper was produced using a [[Cyclostyle (copier)|cyclostyle]], and then moved to a printing press.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ |page=120|quote=''The Doon School Weekly'' became an important feature of the school life and for many boys an education in itself. For the first three years the ''Weekly'' was cyclostyled. While this was not as neat as printing, it had the advantages that it was easy to reproduce drawings.}}</ref>  ''The Doon School Weekly'' has had a number of student contributors who went on to become authors, politicians and journalists. The list includes Booker Prize-nominee [[Amitav Ghosh]] (class of 1972); playwright, poet and novelist [[Vikram Seth]] (class of 1970); a number of staff writers for ''[[The Times of India]]'' newspaper such as [[Swaminathan Aiyar]] and veteran editor [[B G Verghese]], including broadcaster [[Karan Thapar]] (class of 1971), historian [[Ramchandra Guha]] (class of 1973), and politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] (class of 1967); and Hindi language writer [[Vishvjit Singh]] (class of 1964); Foreign Secretary [[Uma Shankar Bajpai]] (class of 1936); [[Wajahat Habibullah]] (class of 1963) and [[Inder Pal Khosla]] (class of 1954); television-presenter [[Prannoy Roy]] and [[Tejeshwar Singh]] (class of 1965); and [[Mahmood Farooqui]] (class of 1979).<ref>[[Chhota Hazri]] Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.42</ref><ref>Chhota Hazri Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.153</ref><ref>The Doon School Chronicles (1996) p.55</ref> Former ''Doon School Weekly'' contributors have been editors, reporters or columnists for ''[[The Economic Times]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]''. On April 14, 2018, the ''Weekly'' published its 2,500th edition, commemorating 82 years of its existence. The edition includes contributions from previous chief-editors such as Karan Thapar, Kanti Bajpai, Rahul Bhagat and Govind Dhar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7hK-gHFw8OUC&pg=PA119&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Nf77T_OPCoXzrQetzrDEBg&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=The Corporeal Image: Film, Ethnography, and the Senses|first=David|last=MacDougall|date=20 July 2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ywJr_YysE7wC&pg=PA25&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tf37T5eIOobqrQeHmsTgBg&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=Psychology in International Perspective|first1=U. P.|last1=Gielen|first2=L.|last2=Loeb-Adler|first3=N.|last3=Milgram|date=1 January 1992|publisher=CRC Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and operations==\nThe Weekly's editorial board is staffed by boys between year groups 9 and 12 at the school, with students in their final year leading the publication and taking key decisions. The selection process for the editorial board is competitive and consists of a written examination and personal interview with the board's leadership. The editor-in-chief, appointed by the school's administration, is the publication's chief executive and is responsible for content and day-to-day operations. He is assisted by the editors, the second-highest positions on the Editorial Board, who are also students in their final year of school. The length of a standard issue of the ''Weekly'' is 6-8 pages on legal-size ivory white paper. A special edition , released on the Saturday of the school's annual Founder's Day, is printed in the form of a magazine. The ''Weekly'' is accessible in print on the school's premises, and is also available online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/|title=Past Weeklies|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former members==\n*[[Vikram Seth]] ('69, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, poet, librettist and playwright <ref name=\"auto\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.24</ref>\n*[[Swaminathan Aiyar]] ('60, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 former India correspondent of ''[[The Economist]]''; editor of ''[[The Economic Times]]'' and ''[[The Times of India]]''\n*[[Amitav Ghosh]] ('73, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, former editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Ramchandra Guha]] ('73, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Historian <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Karan Thapar]] ('71, Editor-in-chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster for [[CNBC]], [[BBC]] & [[CNN-IBN]] <ref name=\"auto1\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.25</ref>\n*[[Prannoy Roy]] ('64, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Founder of [[New Delhi Television]] <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.27</ref>\n*[[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] ('58, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 former [[Union Cabinet]] minister for [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Karan Singh]] ('49, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rajya Sabha]] member <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Naveen Patnaik]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[List of Chief Ministers of Odisha|Chief Minister of Odisha]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Vishvjit Singh]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Poet and member of [[Indian National Congress]] <ref name=\"auto2\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.28</ref>\n*[[Wajahat Habibullah]] ('63, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Information Commissioner|Chief Information Commissioner of India]] and chairman of the [[National Minorities Commission]] <ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n*[[B G Verghese]] ('58, Contributor) Editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' (1982\u201386) and ''[[The Times of India]]'' (1986\u20132005); [[Ramon Magsaysay Award]] winner <ref name=\"auto3\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.33</ref>\n*[[Tejeshwar Singh]] ('65, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Indian publisher, newscaster <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]] ('83, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster, news-presenter for [[New Delhi Television]] (NDTV) <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Ardashir Vakil]] ('78, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.32</ref>\n*Govind Dhar ('97, Editor-in-Chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Travel journalist and magazine editor, former editor of the Robb Report India{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===Further reading===\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=jc-9-rsFLxQC&pg=PA241&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false  Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School] by Sanjay Srivastava, Routledge (1995)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=vUnF8fl2dzcC&pg=PA229&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false An Indian Englishman] by [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] (2008)\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=no |s=The Doon School Weekly |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School Weekly }}\n{{Portal|Journalism}}\n*[http://www.doonschool.com Official website]\n*[http://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/past-weeklies/ Repository of past weeklies] on official website\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School Weekly, The}}\n[[Category:The Doon School]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1936]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in India]]\n[[Category:Student magazines]]\n[[Category:High school newspapers]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper |\nname = The Doon School Weekly |\nimage = The Doon School Weekly.jpg |\ntype = [[Weekly newspaper|Weekly]] [[student newspaper]] |\nowners = [[The Doon School]]|\nformat = [[Compact (newspaper)|Compact]] |\nfoundation = 1936 by [[Arthur Foot]]|\npolitical = None|\nlanguage = English|\npublisher  =Indian Public Schools' Society| \nheadquarters = Publications Room, Arts and Media Centre<br>[[The Doon School]]<br>[[Dehradun]]-248001<br>India |\ncirculation = c. 600 |\noclc = 224047237 |\nwebsite = http://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/\n}}\n\n'''''The Doon School Weekly''''' (informally '''''Weekly''''') is a [[student newspaper]] produced by and for the students of [[The Doon School]].<ref>https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon</ref> It was established in 1936, a year after the school's founding, by the first headmaster [[Arthur Foot]]. The ''Weekly'' is the oldest and flagship publication of the school, and the newspaper's constitution grants it [[editorial independence]].<ref name=>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |last=Futehally |first=Laeeq |date=24 February 2002 |website=The Hindu |access-date=1 March 2012}}</ref> The paper, distributed every Saturday morning, carries a mix of reports on school activities, trips or expeditions, opinion pieces, critique of school policies, interviews of visiting speakers, student polls, crossword, cartoons, and creative writing, including short stories, poetry, satire or personal essays. The alumni keep up to date with the developments at school through the newspaper, which is also published online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2015/state-editions/a-beloved-teacher-of-the-doon-school.html|title=A beloved teacher of the Doon School|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref>  Notable alumni in the fields of literature, journalist, politics and academia have been former editors of the publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/from-doon-school-to-jnanpith-award--amitav-ghosh---s-amazing-journey.html|title=From Doon School to Jnanpith Award: Amitav Ghosh\u2019s amazing journey|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/features/nature-cricket-literature-history-1502519395.html|title=Of nature, cricket, literature and history|date=29 October 2017}}</ref> The Weekly's sister publications at the school are ''Infinity'', ''The Doon School Information Review'', ''The Circle'', and ''The Yearbook''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimonen|first=Eija|title=Education and Society in Comparative Context|year=2015|publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]|location=|isbn=9789463003735|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=SmM-CwAAQBAJ&|page=143|quote=In addition to producing a conventional yearbook, the students also produced other periodicals, such as the school's special publications: ''The Doon School Information Review''...and the scientific bi-annual ''The Echo'' and ''Cosmos''.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFounded by Arthu Foot in 1936, ''The Doon School Weekly'' is owned by Indian Public Schools' Society, the governing society of [[The Doon School]]. For the first three years of its existence, the newspaper was produced using a [[Cyclostyle (copier)|cyclostyle]], and then moved to a printing press.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ |page=120|quote=''The Doon School Weekly'' became an important feature of the school life and for many boys an education in itself. For the first three years the ''Weekly'' was cyclostyled. While this was not as neat as printing, it had the advantages that it was easy to reproduce drawings.}}</ref>  ''The Doon School Weekly'' has had a number of student contributors who went on to become authors, politicians and journalists. The list includes Booker Prize-nominee [[Amitav Ghosh]] (class of 1972); playwright, poet and novelist [[Vikram Seth]] (class of 1970); a number of staff writers for ''[[The Times of India]]'' newspaper such as [[Swaminathan Aiyar]] and veteran editor [[B G Verghese]], including broadcaster [[Karan Thapar]] (class of 1971), historian [[Ramchandra Guha]] (class of 1973), and politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] (class of 1967); and Hindi language writer [[Vishvjit Singh]] (class of 1964); Foreign Secretary [[Uma Shankar Bajpai]] (class of 1936); [[Wajahat Habibullah]] (class of 1963) and [[Inder Pal Khosla]] (class of 1954); television-presenter [[Prannoy Roy]] and [[Tejeshwar Singh]] (class of 1965); and [[Mahmood Farooqui]] (class of 1979).<ref>[[Chhota Hazri]] Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.42</ref><ref>Chhota Hazri Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.153</ref><ref>The Doon School Chronicles (1996) p.55</ref> Former ''Doon School Weekly'' contributors have been editors, reporters or columnists for ''[[The Economic Times]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]''. On April 14, 2018, the ''Weekly'' published its 2,500th edition, commemorating 82 years of its existence. The edition includes contributions from previous chief-editors such as Karan Thapar, Kanti Bajpai, Rahul Bhagat and Govind Dhar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7hK-gHFw8OUC&pg=PA119&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Nf77T_OPCoXzrQetzrDEBg&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=The Corporeal Image: Film, Ethnography, and the Senses|first=David|last=MacDougall|date=20 July 2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ywJr_YysE7wC&pg=PA25&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tf37T5eIOobqrQeHmsTgBg&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=Psychology in International Perspective|first1=U. P.|last1=Gielen|first2=L.|last2=Loeb-Adler|first3=N.|last3=Milgram|date=1 January 1992|publisher=CRC Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and operations==\nThe Weekly's editorial board is staffed by boys between year groups 9 and 12 at the school, with students in their final year leading the publication and taking key decisions. The selection process for the editorial board is competitive and consists of a written examination and personal interview with the board's leadership. The editor-in-chief, appointed by the school's administration, is the publication's chief executive and is responsible for content and day-to-day operations. He is assisted by the editors, the second-highest positions on the Editorial Board, who are also students in their final year of school. The length of a standard issue of the ''Weekly'' is 6-8 pages on legal-size ivory white paper. A special edition , released on the Saturday of the school's annual Founder's Day, is printed in the form of a magazine. The ''Weekly'' is accessible in print on the school's premises, and is also available online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/|title=Past Weeklies|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former members==\n*[[Vikram Seth]] ('69, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, poet, librettist and playwright <ref name=\"auto\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.24</ref>\n*[[Swaminathan Aiyar]] ('60, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 former India correspondent of ''[[The Economist]]''; editor of ''[[The Economic Times]]'' and ''[[The Times of India]]''\n*[[Amitav Ghosh]] ('73, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, former editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Ramchandra Guha]] ('73, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Historian <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Karan Thapar]] ('71, Editor-in-chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster for [[CNBC]], [[BBC]] & [[CNN-IBN]] <ref name=\"auto1\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.25</ref>\n*[[Prannoy Roy]] ('64, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Founder of [[New Delhi Television]] <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.27</ref>\n*[[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] ('58, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 former [[Union Cabinet]] minister for [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Karan Singh]] ('49, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rajya Sabha]] member <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Naveen Patnaik]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[List of Chief Ministers of Odisha|Chief Minister of Odisha]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Vishvjit Singh]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Poet and member of [[Indian National Congress]] <ref name=\"auto2\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.28</ref>\n*[[Wajahat Habibullah]] ('63, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Information Commissioner|Chief Information Commissioner of India]] and chairman of the [[National Minorities Commission]] <ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n*[[B G Verghese]] ('58, Contributor) Editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' (1982\u201386) and ''[[The Times of India]]'' (1986\u20132005); [[Ramon Magsaysay Award]] winner <ref name=\"auto3\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.33</ref>\n*[[Tejeshwar Singh]] ('65, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Indian publisher, newscaster <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]] ('83, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster, news-presenter for [[New Delhi Television]] (NDTV) <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Ardashir Vakil]] ('78, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.32</ref>\n*Govind Dhar ('97, Editor-in-Chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Travel journalist and magazine editor, former editor of the Robb Report India{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===Further reading===\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=jc-9-rsFLxQC&pg=PA241&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false  Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School] by Sanjay Srivastava, Routledge (1995)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=vUnF8fl2dzcC&pg=PA229&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false An Indian Englishman] by [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] (2008)\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=no |s=The Doon School Weekly |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School Weekly }}\n{{Portal|Journalism}}\n*[http://www.doonschool.com Official website]\n*[http://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/past-weeklies/ Repository of past weeklies] on official website\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School Weekly, The}}\n[[Category:The Doon School]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1936]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in India]]\n[[Category:Student magazines]]\n[[Category:High school newspapers]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Tabfelz", "label": "safe", "comment": "*ism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doon_School_Weekly"}
{"title_page": "Italy v Brazil (1982 FIFA World Cup)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = 1982 FIFA World Cup<br>Group C\n|                   image =[[ File:Sarri\u00e0.jpg|200px]]\n| caption = The [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0]] held the match \n|                   event = [[1982 FIFA World Cup]]\n|                   team1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n|        team1association = {{flagicon|ITA|size=30px}}\n|              team1score = 3\n|                   team2 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]\n|        team2association = {{flagicon|BRA|size=30px}}\n|              team2score = 2\n|                    date = 5 July 1982\n|                 stadium = [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0|Estadio Sarri\u00e1]]\n|                    city = [[Barcelona]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a = \n|                 referee = [[Abraham Klein (referee)|Abraham Klein]] ([[Israel Football Association|Israel]])\n|              attendance = 44,000\n|                 weather = \n}}\n'''Italy v Brazil''' was a football match that took place between [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Italy national football team|Italy]] at [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0|Estadio Sarri\u00e1]], [[Barcelona]] on 5 July 1982. It was the final second round [[group stage]] match for Group C in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]]. The match was won by Italy 3\u20132, with Italian [[Forward (association football)|striker]] [[Paolo Rossi]] scoring a [[hat-trick]]. The result eliminated Brazil from the tournament while Italy would go on to win it. The match has been described as one of the greatest football matches of all time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duarte|first1=Fernando|title=Brazil lost that Italy game in 1982 but won a place in history \u2013 Falc\u00e3o|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/may/30/brazil-falcao-1982-world-cup-italy|website=The Guardian|accessdate=20 May 2015|date=30 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilson|first1=Jonathan|title=Italy 3-2 Brazil, 1982: the day naivety, not football itself, died|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/jul/25/italy-brazil-1982|website=The Guardian|accessdate=20 May 2015|date=25 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lewis|first1=Tim|title=1982: Why Brazil V Italy Was One Of Football's Greatest Ever Matches|url=http://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/news/a6396/1982-why-brazil-v-italy-was-one-of-footballs-greatest-ever-matches/|website=Esquire|accessdate=10 February 2018|date=11 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-match==\nBrazil had won all four of their matches prior, including comprehensive wins over [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] (4\u20131) and [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] (4\u20130), and were the pre-tournament favourites.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/worldcup2006/history/events/1982.html |title=1982 Spain |publisher=CBC |date= |accessdate=22 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216135130/http://www.cbc.ca/sports/worldcup2006/history/events/1982.html |archivedate=16 December 2008 | work=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rossi wakes to flatten favourites|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/matches/match=788/index.html|accessdate=30 June 2011|newspaper=FIFA}}</ref> They were praised for their attacking style. Italy had come off an impressive 2\u20131 victory over [[Diego Maradona]]'s Argentina. In the first round, however, Italy drew all three matches and qualified for the second round over [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] on goals scored. Italy's striker Rossi had failed to score up to that point and there was considerable debate about whether he should be on the team, compounded with the fact that he had returned from a two-year ban following his involvement in the [[Totonero 1980]] match-fixing scandal. Italy was forced to play for a win to reach the semi-final, due to a worse goal difference, as Brazil had defeated Argentina 3\u20131 before the decisive match against Italy.\n\n==Match==\n===Summary===\nThe match put Brazil's attack against Italy's defense, with the majority of the game played around the Italian area, with the Italian midfielders and defenders returning the repeated set volleys of Brazilian shooters such as [[Zico]], [[S\u00f3crates]] and [[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]]. Italian centre back [[Claudio Gentile]] was assigned to mark Brazilian striker Zico, earning a yellow card and a suspension for the semi-final. [[Paolo Rossi]] opened the scoring when he headed in [[Antonio Cabrini]]'s cross with just five minutes played. S\u00f3crates equalised for Brazil seven minutes later. In the twenty-fifth minute Rossi stepped past [[Leovegildo Lins da Gama J\u00fanior|J\u00fanior]], intercepted a pass from [[Toninho Cerezo|Cerezo]] across the Brazilians' goal, and drilled the shot home. The Brazilians threw everything in search of another equalizer, while Italy defended bravely. On 68 minutes, [[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] collected a pass from J\u00fanior and as Cerezo's dummy run distracted three defenders, fired home from 20 yards out. Now Italy had gained the lead twice thanks to Rossi's goals, and Brazil had come back twice. At 2\u20132, Brazil would have been through on goal difference, but in the 74th minute, a poor clearance from an Italian corner kick went back to the Brazilian six-yard line where Rossi and [[Francesco Graziani]] were waiting. Both aimed at the same shot, Rossi connecting to get a [[hat trick]] and sending Italy into the lead for good. In the 86th minute [[Giancarlo Antognoni]] scored a fourth goal for Italy, but it was wrongly disallowed for offside. In the dying moments [[Dino Zoff]] made a miraculous save to deny [[Oscar (footballer, born 1954)|Oscar]] a goal, ensuring that Italy advanced to the semi-final where they would meet [[Poland national football team|Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/news/a6396/1982-why-brazil-v-italy-was-one-of-footballs-greatest-ever-matches/|title=1982: Why Brazil V Italy Was One Of Football's Greatest Ever Matches|publisher=Esquire.co.uk|date=11 July 2014|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=John|last=Foot|authorlink=John Foot (historian)|title=Winning at All Costs: A Scandalous History of Italian Soccer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NBufCsXpkVkC&pg=PA470&lpg=PA470&dq=italy+brazil+antognoni+goal&source=bl&ots=btSCQBVbNY&sig=qo4llpQdtc_qPbcBhfRttqx0XYY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0_OyU9WRMYjV4QTZ6oC4Ag&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=italy%20brazil%20antognoni%20goal&f=false|page=470|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{footballbox\n|date = 5 July 1982\n|time = 17:15 [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 3\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=294/match=788/report.html\n|team2 = {{fb|BRA|1968}}\n|goals1 = [[Paolo Rossi|Rossi]] {{goal|5||25||74}}\n|goals2 = [[S\u00f3crates]] {{goal|12}}<br />[[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] {{goal|68}}\n|stadium = [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0|Estadio Sarri\u00e1]], [[Barcelona]]\n|attendance = 44,000\n|referee = [[Abraham Klein (referee)|Abraham Klein]] ([[Israel Football Association|Israel]])\n}}\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _italy1982-90\n | pattern_b  = _ita82\n | pattern_ra = _italy1982-90\n | pattern_so = _italia_cm1994\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 3120CC\n | title      = Italy\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _ adidasbrasil2\n | pattern_b  = _ adidasbrasil\n | pattern_ra = _ adidasbrasil1\n | pattern_sh = _adidaswhite\n | pattern_so = _brasil 1978\n | leftarm    = FFFF00\n | body       = FFFF00\n | rightarm   = FFFF00\n | shorts     = 0047AB\n | socks      = FFFFFF\n | title      = Brazil\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) \n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' ||[[Antonio Cabrini]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' ||[[Fulvio Collovati]] || || {{suboff|34}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''6''' ||[[Claudio Gentile]] || {{yel|13}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''7''' ||[[Gaetano Scirea]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''9''' ||[[Giancarlo Antognoni]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''||[[Gabriele Oriali]] || {{yel|78}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''||[[Marco Tardelli]]  || || {{suboff|75}} \n|-\n|MF ||'''16'''||[[Bruno Conti]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''19'''||[[Francesco Graziani]] \n|-\n|CF ||'''20'''||[[Paolo Rossi]] \n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''12'''||[[Ivano Bordon]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Giuseppe Bergomi]] || || {{subon|34}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''|| [[Giampiero Marini]] || || {{subon|75}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||[[Franco Causio]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''18'''||[[Alessandro Altobelli]] \n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%; margin: auto;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Waldir Peres]] \n|-\n|RB ||'''2''' ||[[Jos\u00e9 Leandro Ferreira|Leandro]] \n|-\n|CH ||'''3''' ||[[Oscar (footballer, born 1954)|Oscar]] \n|-\n|CH ||'''4''' ||[[Luiz Carlos Ferreira|Luizinho]] \n|-\n|CM ||'''5''' ||[[Toninho Cerezo]] \n|-\n|LB ||'''6''' ||[[Leovegildo Lins da Gama J\u00fanior|J\u00fanior]]  \n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||[[S\u00f3crates]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) \n|-\n|SS ||'''10'''||[[Zico]] \n|-\n|LM ||'''11'''||[[\u00c9der Aleixo de Assis|\u00c9der]] \n|-\n|RM ||'''15'''||[[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] \n|-\n|CF ||'''9''' ||[[Serginho Chulapa|Serginho]] || || {{suboff|69}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''12'''||[[Paulo S\u00e9rgio de Oliveira Lima|Paulo S\u00e9rgio]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''13'''||[[Edevaldo de Freitas|Edevaldo]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''14'''||[[Juninho Fonseca|Juninho]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' ||[[Paulo Isidoro]]  || || {{subon|69}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''19'''||[[Carlos Renato Frederico|Renato]] \n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Tel\u00ea Santana]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%; font-size:90%;\"\n|\n'''[[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referee]]s:'''\n<br />[[Thomson Chan|Chan Tam Sun]] ([[Hong Kong Football Association|Hong Kong]])\n<br />[[Bogdan Dotchev]] ([[Bulgarian Football Union|Bulgaria]]) \n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes.\n*Five named substitutes.\n*Maximum of two substitutions.\n|}\n\n==Impact==\nThe result was seen by many as not only a defeat for Brazil, but a defeat of their attacking philosophy by the less talented but more organized Italians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story/_/id/897472/rewind-to-1982:-brilliant-brazil's-brush-with-greatness?cc=5739 |title=Rewind to 1982: Brilliant Brazil's brush with greatness \u2013 ESPN Soccernet |publisher=Soccernet.espn.go.com |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>\nThis match has since then been labeled by the Brazilian press as the 'Sarri\u00e0 Tragedy' (Portuguese: ''A trag\u00e9dia do Sarri\u00e0'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/writers/tim_vickery/07/24/brazil.reax/1.html |title=The great debate (cont'd) |publisher=Sportsillustrated.cnn.com |date=24 July 2007 |accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe result of the match had a profound and lasting impact on Brazilian football and fundamentally changed its philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/esporte/fk1705200208.htm |title=Com derrota, nasceu futebol de resultados |date=17 May 2002 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Luizinho, Brazil's centre back in 1982, the defeat changed Brazilian coaches' way of thinking, leading to a new, destructive philosophy based on defensive, counter attacking football - the style of football played by the Italians against the Brazilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndmais.com.br/esportes/35-anos-de-sarria-o-impacto-da-copa-de-1982-no-futebol-mundial/amp/ |title=35 anos de Sarri\u00e1: O impacto da Copa de 1982 no futebol mundial |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs described by sports journalist Tim Vickery: \"For many Brazilian coaches, the failure of that 1982 side to win the World Cup (...) served as proof for ideas that had been kicking around for a while - starting with a 5-1 massacre at the hands of Belgium in 1963, confirmed by the defeat by Holland in the 1974 World Cup. The physical development of the game, it was thought, meant that traditional methods had to be revised. Brazilian players had to bulk up - Rubens Minelli, the most successful domestic coach of the 70s, wanted his team to be made up of six footers. And with less space on the field, the future of football lay in the counter attack, rather than elaborate attempts to pass through midfield.\" He continues by stating that \"these thoughts have carried a lot of weight in the Brazilian game. They help explain why a succession of Brazil sides have caught the eye for explosive breaks down the flanks rather than for the succession of midfield triangles that enraptured Cappa and everyone else in 1982. When former Middlesbrough left-back Branco was in charge of Brazil\u2019s youth sides, he told me that right from the start of the process the search for big, strong youngsters was a priority. Brazilian coaches, meanwhile, became fond of spouting the statistic that the chances of a goal are reduced if the move contains more than seven passes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2011/08/brazil_have_never_looked_the_s.html |title=Brazil fail to rediscover winning formula |date=15 August 2011 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> He also earlier stated in 2006 that \"had Brazil won the trophy in 1982 the team would be more than a fond memory. They might be the blueprint for future sides, because winners are always copied.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4937698.stm |title=Football is the poorer for the passing last week of Tele Santana. |date=24 April 2006 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFurther success in 1994 and 2002 in mostly pragmatic styles cemented the new philosophy and practically buried the traditional passing style further into the past.\n\nThe rise of [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiki-taka Tiki-Taka], a style of football partly based on moving triangles, positional interchange and intricate passing - highly reminiscent of the old Brazilian passing style, embodied by the 1982 team - has helped recover some of the prestige of the 1982 team in the country. The crushing defeat of the Brazilian counterattacking style by tiki-taka teams, namely [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_FIFA_Club_World_Cup_Final the 4-0 defeat of Santos to Barcelona] and the [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brazil_v_Germany_(2014_FIFA_World_Cup) 7-1 Brazilian defeat to Germany at home at the World Cup in 2014] laid bare how Brazilian football had been left behind. As a result, the country's football philosophy has been slowly returning to the old intricate passing style in the last few years, as recent success by [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_Copa_Libertadores_Finals Gr\u00eamio]  and [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Clube_de_Regatas_do_Flamengo_season Flamengo] have shown.\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Brazil\u2013Italy football rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1982 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Brazil national football team matches}}\n{{Italy national football team matches}}\n\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup]]\n[[Category:Brazil national football team matches|1982]]\n[[Category:Italy national football team matches|1981]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup matches]]\n[[Category:Brazil at the 1982 FIFA World Cup|Italy]]\n[[Category:Italy at the 1982 FIFA World Cup]]\n[[Category:Football in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:1980s in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:July 1982 sports events in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = 1982 FIFA World Cup<br>Group C\n|                   image =[[ File:Sarri\u00e0.jpg|200px]]\n| caption = The [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0]] held the match \n|                   event = [[1982 FIFA World Cup]]\n|                   team1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n|        team1association = {{flagicon|ITA|size=30px}}\n|              team1score = 3\n|                   team2 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]\n|        team2association = {{flagicon|BRA|size=30px}}\n|              team2score = 2\n|                    date = 5 July 1982\n|                 stadium = [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0|Estadio Sarri\u00e1]]\n|                    city = [[Barcelona]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a = \n|                 referee = [[Abraham Klein (referee)|Abraham Klein]] ([[Israel Football Association|Israel]])\n|              attendance = 44,000\n|                 weather = \n}}\n'''Italy v Brazil''' was a football match that took place between [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Italy national football team|Italy]] at [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0|Estadio Sarri\u00e1]], [[Barcelona]] on 5 July 1982. It was the final second round [[group stage]] match for Group C in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]]. The match was won by Italy 3\u20132, with Italian [[Forward (association football)|striker]] [[Paolo Rossi]] scoring a [[hat-trick]]. The result eliminated Brazil from the tournament while Italy would go on to win it. The match has been described as one of the greatest football matches of all time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duarte|first1=Fernando|title=Brazil lost that Italy game in 1982 but won a place in history \u2013 Falc\u00e3o|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/may/30/brazil-falcao-1982-world-cup-italy|website=The Guardian|accessdate=20 May 2015|date=30 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilson|first1=Jonathan|title=Italy 3-2 Brazil, 1982: the day naivety, not football itself, died|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/jul/25/italy-brazil-1982|website=The Guardian|accessdate=20 May 2015|date=25 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lewis|first1=Tim|title=1982: Why Brazil V Italy Was One Of Football's Greatest Ever Matches|url=http://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/news/a6396/1982-why-brazil-v-italy-was-one-of-footballs-greatest-ever-matches/|website=Esquire|accessdate=10 February 2018|date=11 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-match==\nBrazil had won all four of their matches prior, including comprehensive wins over [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] (4\u20131) and [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] (4\u20130), and were the pre-tournament favourites.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/worldcup2006/history/events/1982.html |title=1982 Spain |publisher=CBC |date= |accessdate=22 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216135130/http://www.cbc.ca/sports/worldcup2006/history/events/1982.html |archivedate=16 December 2008 | work=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rossi wakes to flatten favourites|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/matches/match=788/index.html|accessdate=30 June 2011|newspaper=FIFA}}</ref> They were praised for their attacking style. Italy had come off an impressive 2\u20131 victory over [[Diego Maradona]]'s Argentina. In the first round, however, Italy drew all three matches and qualified for the second round over [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] on goals scored. Italy's striker Rossi had failed to score up to that point and there was considerable debate about whether he should be on the team, compounded with the fact that he had returned from a two-year ban following his involvement in the [[Totonero 1980]] match-fixing scandal. Italy was forced to play for a win to reach the semi-final, due to a worse goal difference, as Brazil had defeated Argentina 3\u20131 before the decisive match against Italy.\n\n==Match==\n===Summary===\nThe match put Brazil's attack against Italy's defense, with the majority of the game played around the Italian area, with the Italian midfielders and defenders returning the repeated set volleys of Brazilian shooters such as [[Zico]], [[S\u00f3crates]] and [[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]]. Italian centre back [[Claudio Gentile]] was assigned to mark Brazilian striker Zico, earning a yellow card and a suspension for the semi-final. [[Paolo Rossi]] opened the scoring when he headed in [[Antonio Cabrini]]'s cross with just five minutes played. S\u00f3crates equalised for Brazil seven minutes later. In the twenty-fifth minute Rossi stepped past [[Leovegildo Lins da Gama J\u00fanior|J\u00fanior]], intercepted a pass from [[Toninho Cerezo|Cerezo]] across the Brazilians' goal, and drilled the shot home. The Brazilians threw everything in search of another equalizer, while Italy defended bravely. On 68 minutes, [[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] collected a pass from J\u00fanior and as Cerezo's dummy run distracted three defenders, fired home from 20 yards out. Now Italy had gained the lead twice thanks to Rossi's goals, and Brazil had come back twice. At 2\u20132, Brazil would have been through on goal difference, but in the 74th minute, a poor clearance from an Italian corner kick went back to the Brazilian six-yard line where Rossi and [[Francesco Graziani]] were waiting. Both aimed at the same shot, Rossi connecting to get a [[hat trick]] and sending Italy into the lead for good. In the 86th minute [[Giancarlo Antognoni]] scored a fourth goal for Italy, but it was wrongly disallowed for offside. In the dying moments [[Dino Zoff]] made a miraculous save to deny [[Oscar (footballer, born 1954)|Oscar]] a goal, ensuring that Italy advanced to the semi-final where they would meet [[Poland national football team|Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/news/a6396/1982-why-brazil-v-italy-was-one-of-footballs-greatest-ever-matches/|title=1982: Why Brazil V Italy Was One Of Football's Greatest Ever Matches|publisher=Esquire.co.uk|date=11 July 2014|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=John|last=Foot|authorlink=John Foot (historian)|title=Winning at All Costs: A Scandalous History of Italian Soccer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NBufCsXpkVkC&pg=PA470&lpg=PA470&dq=italy+brazil+antognoni+goal&source=bl&ots=btSCQBVbNY&sig=qo4llpQdtc_qPbcBhfRttqx0XYY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0_OyU9WRMYjV4QTZ6oC4Ag&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=italy%20brazil%20antognoni%20goal&f=false|page=470|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{footballbox\n|date = 5 July 1982\n|time = 17:15 [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 3\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=294/match=788/report.html\n|team2 = {{fb|BRA|1968}}\n|goals1 = [[Paolo Rossi|Rossi]] {{goal|5||25||74}}\n|goals2 = [[S\u00f3crates]] {{goal|12}}<br />[[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] {{goal|68}}\n|stadium = [[Estadi de Sarri\u00e0|Estadio Sarri\u00e1]], [[Barcelona]]\n|attendance = 44,000\n|referee = [[Abraham Klein (referee)|Abraham Klein]] ([[Israel Football Association|Israel]])\n}}\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _italy1982-90\n | pattern_b  = _ita82\n | pattern_ra = _italy1982-90\n | pattern_so = _italia_cm1994\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 3120CC\n | title      = Italy\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _ adidasbrasil2\n | pattern_b  = _ adidasbrasil\n | pattern_ra = _ adidasbrasil1\n | pattern_sh = _adidaswhite\n | pattern_so = _brasil 1978\n | leftarm    = FFFF00\n | body       = FFFF00\n | rightarm   = FFFF00\n | shorts     = 0047AB\n | socks      = FFFFFF\n | title      = Brazil\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) \n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' ||[[Antonio Cabrini]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' ||[[Fulvio Collovati]] || || {{suboff|34}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''6''' ||[[Claudio Gentile]] || {{yel|13}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''7''' ||[[Gaetano Scirea]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''9''' ||[[Giancarlo Antognoni]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''||[[Gabriele Oriali]] || {{yel|78}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''||[[Marco Tardelli]]  || || {{suboff|75}} \n|-\n|MF ||'''16'''||[[Bruno Conti]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''19'''||[[Francesco Graziani]] \n|-\n|CF ||'''20'''||[[Paolo Rossi]] \n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''12'''||[[Ivano Bordon]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Giuseppe Bergomi]] || || {{subon|34}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''|| [[Giampiero Marini]] || || {{subon|75}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||[[Franco Causio]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''18'''||[[Alessandro Altobelli]] \n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%; margin: auto;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Waldir Peres]] \n|-\n|RB ||'''2''' ||[[Jos\u00e9 Leandro Ferreira|Leandro]] \n|-\n|CH ||'''3''' ||[[Oscar (footballer, born 1954)|Oscar]] \n|-\n|CH ||'''4''' ||[[Luiz Carlos Ferreira|Luizinho]] \n|-\n|CM ||'''5''' ||[[Toninho Cerezo]] \n|-\n|LB ||'''6''' ||[[Leovegildo Lins da Gama J\u00fanior|J\u00fanior]]  \n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||[[S\u00f3crates]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) \n|-\n|SS ||'''10'''||[[Zico]] \n|-\n|LM ||'''11'''||[[\u00c9der Aleixo de Assis|\u00c9der]] \n|-\n|RM ||'''15'''||[[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] \n|-\n|CF ||'''9''' ||[[Serginho Chulapa|Serginho]] || || {{suboff|69}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''12'''||[[Paulo S\u00e9rgio de Oliveira Lima|Paulo S\u00e9rgio]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''13'''||[[Edevaldo de Freitas|Edevaldo]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''14'''||[[Juninho Fonseca|Juninho]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' ||[[Paulo Isidoro]]  || || {{subon|69}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''19'''||[[Carlos Renato Frederico|Renato]] \n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Tel\u00ea Santana]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%; font-size:90%;\"\n|\n'''[[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referee]]s:'''\n<br />[[Thomson Chan|Chan Tam Sun]] ([[Hong Kong Football Association|Hong Kong]])\n<br />[[Bogdan Dotchev]] ([[Bulgarian Football Union|Bulgaria]]) \n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes.\n*Five named substitutes.\n*Maximum of two substitutions.\n|}\n\n==Impact==\nThe result was seen by many as not only a defeat for Brazil, but a defeat of their attacking philosophy by the less talented but more organized Italians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story/_/id/897472/rewind-to-1982:-brilliant-brazil's-brush-with-greatness?cc=5739 |title=Rewind to 1982: Brilliant Brazil's brush with greatness \u2013 ESPN Soccernet |publisher=Soccernet.espn.go.com |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>\nThis match has since then been labelled by Brazilian press as the 'Sarri\u00e0 Stadium Tragedy' (Portuguese: ''A trag\u00e9dia do Sarri\u00e0'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/writers/tim_vickery/07/24/brazil.reax/1.html |title=The great debate (cont'd) |publisher=Sportsillustrated.cnn.com |date=24 July 2007 |accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe result of the match had a profound and lasting impact on Brazilian football and fundamentally changed its philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/esporte/fk1705200208.htm |title=Com derrota, nasceu futebol de resultados |date=17 May 2002 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Luizinho, Brazil's centre back in 1982, the defeat changed Brazilian coaches' way of thinking, leading to a new, destructive philosophy based on defensive, counter attacking football - the style of football played by the Italians against the Brazilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndmais.com.br/esportes/35-anos-de-sarria-o-impacto-da-copa-de-1982-no-futebol-mundial/amp/ |title=35 anos de Sarri\u00e1: O impacto da Copa de 1982 no futebol mundial |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs described by sports journalist Tim Vickery: \"For many Brazilian coaches, the failure of that 1982 side to win the World Cup (...) served as proof for ideas that had been kicking around for a while - starting with a 5-1 massacre at the hands of Belgium in 1963, confirmed by the defeat by Holland in the 1974 World Cup. The physical development of the game, it was thought, meant that traditional methods had to be revised. Brazilian players had to bulk up - Rubens Minelli, the most successful domestic coach of the 70s, wanted his team to be made up of six footers. And with less space on the field, the future of football lay in the counter attack, rather than elaborate attempts to pass through midfield.\" He continues by stating that \"these thoughts have carried a lot of weight in the Brazilian game. They help explain why a succession of Brazil sides have caught the eye for explosive breaks down the flanks rather than for the succession of midfield triangles that enraptured Cappa and everyone else in 1982. When former Middlesbrough left-back Branco was in charge of Brazil\u2019s youth sides, he told me that right from the start of the process the search for big, strong youngsters was a priority. Brazilian coaches, meanwhile, became fond of spouting the statistic that the chances of a goal are reduced if the move contains more than seven passes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2011/08/brazil_have_never_looked_the_s.html |title=Brazil fail to rediscover winning formula |date=15 August 2011 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> He also earlier stated in 2006 that \"had Brazil won the trophy in 1982 the team would be more than a fond memory. They might be the blueprint for future sides, because winners are always copied.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4937698.stm |title=Football is the poorer for the passing last week of Tele Santana. |date=24 April 2006 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFurther success in 1994 and 2002 in mostly pragmatic styles cemented the new philosophy and practically buried the traditional passing style further into the past.\n\nThe rise of [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiki-taka Tiki-Taka], a style of football partly based on moving triangles, positional interchange and intricate passing - highly reminiscent of the old Brazilian passing style, embodied by the 1982 team - has helped recover some of the prestige of the 1982 team in the country. The crushing defeat of the Brazilian counterattacking style by tiki-taka teams, namely [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_FIFA_Club_World_Cup_Final the 4-0 defeat of Santos to Barcelona] and the [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brazil_v_Germany_(2014_FIFA_World_Cup) 7-1 Brazilian defeat to Germany at home at the World Cup in 2014] laid bare how Brazilian football had been left behind. As a result, the country's football philosophy has been slowly returning to the old intricate passing style in the last few years, as recent success by [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_Copa_Libertadores_Finals Gr\u00eamio]  and [https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Clube_de_Regatas_do_Flamengo_season Flamengo] have shown.\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Brazil\u2013Italy football rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1982 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Brazil national football team matches}}\n{{Italy national football team matches}}\n\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup]]\n[[Category:Brazil national football team matches|1982]]\n[[Category:Italy national football team matches|1981]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup matches]]\n[[Category:Brazil at the 1982 FIFA World Cup|Italy]]\n[[Category:Italy at the 1982 FIFA World Cup]]\n[[Category:Football in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:1980s in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:July 1982 sports events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Fdief", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italy_v_Brazil_(1982_FIFA_World_Cup)"}
{"title_page": "Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest", "text_new": "{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name = Turkey\n| Member station = [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation]] (TRT)\n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title = National final\n | 1975\n | 1978\n | 1980\u20131993\n | 1995\u20132002\n | 2004\u20132005\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title = Internal selection\n | 2003\n | 2006\u20132012\n}}\n| ESC apps = 34 (33 finals)\n| ESC first = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975]]\n| ESC last = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]]\n| ESC best = 1st: [[Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]]\n| ESC worst = Last: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1983|1983]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]]\n| Nul points = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1983|1983]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]]\n| Website = [http://www.trteurovision.eu TRT page]\n| EBU page = https://eurovision.tv/country/turkey\n| Current = 2012\n}}\n\n'''Turkey''' has participated in the '''[[Eurovision Song Contest]]''' 34 times since [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975]]. Since the introduction of the semi-finals in {{escyr|2004}}, the only year that Turkey participated and failed to advance to the finals was in {{escyr|2011}}. Turkey won the contest once in {{escyr|2003}}, and hosted the {{escyr|2004}} contest in [[Istanbul]].\n\nTurkey finished last on its debut at the contest in 1975, and went on to finish last with \"[[nul points]]\" in {{escyr|1983}} and {{escyr|1987}}. They reached the top ten for the first time in 1986. [[\u015eebnem Paker]] achieved the country's first top five result in {{escyr|1997}}, finishing third with the song \"[[Dinle]]\".\n\nThey went on to achieve five more top five placements after the introduction of the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest#Rule changes by year|free language rule]] and televoting, with [[Sertab Erener]] giving Turkey its first victory in {{escyr|2003}} with the song \"[[Everyway That I Can]]\", narrowly defeating [[Belgium in the Eurovision Song Contest|Belgium]] by two points. Turkey's other top five results are [[Athena (band)|Athena]] ({{escyr|2004}}), [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] ({{escyr|2007}}), [[Hadise]] ({{escyr|2009}}), who all finished fourth, and the [[nu metal]] band [[maNga (band)|maNga]] ({{escyr|2010}}), who finished second.\n\nThe [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]] announced in December 2012 that they would not attend the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013 contest]] in [[Malm\u00f6]], citing dissatisfaction with the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest|rules of the competition]].<ref name=\"wthdrw1\">{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey will not go to Eurovision in Malm\u00f6|url=http://www.esctoday.com/40037/turkey-will-not-be-in-malmo/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=14 December 2012|date=14 December 2012}}</ref> 2013 was the first time since {{escyr|1973}} that there was no television broadcast of the Eurovision Song Contest on TRT. In September 2013, TRT stated a return is unlikely for [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|the 2014 competition]], citing the same reasons.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey: TRT will not participate in Eurovision 2014|url=http://www.esctoday.com/68587/turkey-trt-will-not-participate-in-eurovision-2014/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=7 November 2013|date=7 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"nobroadcast\">{{cite web|title=TRT, Eurovision'u yay\u0131nlamaktan vazge\u00e7ti!|url=https://www.ogunhaber.com/magazin/trt-eurovisionu-yayinlamaktan-vazgecti-145790h.html}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Turkish Radio and Television Corporation involvement in the Eurovision Song Contest ===\nThe national broadcasting service of [[Turkey]], the [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation]] (TRT), was one of the charter members of the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) in 1950 along with eighteen countries around Europe, including [[Tunisia]]. As an intercontinental country (with lands in [[Eastern Thrace]] and [[Western Asia]]), Turkey takes part in a multitude of Western organizations including [[NATO]] as of 1952 and the [[European Economic Community]] as an [[Member State of the European Union#Related states|associate member]] as of 1959.\n\nTRT televised the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] between [[Eurovision Song Contest 1973|1973]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]], even during years in which Turkey was not participating in the contest.\n\n=== 1970s ===\nTurkey participated in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975 Eurovision Song Contest]] held in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]. [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest|Greece]] did not take part in the 1975 Contest for \"unknown reasons\" according to the [[European Broadcasting Union|EBU]], but it was later revealed that the withdrawal was in protest of Turkey's debut and their [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|invasion of Cyprus]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ogaegreece.com/node/150|title=EUROVISION SONG CONTEST 1975|publisher=OGAE Greece|language=Greek|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Raycoff|first=Ivan|author2=Robert Deayom Tobin|title=A Song for Europe|date=July 2007|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing]]|isbn= 978-0-7546-5878-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Eq7nilnv93cC&printsec=frontcover&dq=a+song+for+europe&client=firefox-a&sig=ACfU3U0r2r9IklIU3MfJf6wIZOWTlbgE4A#PPR18,M1|location=[[Aldershot]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]]}}</ref> TRT organized a [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 1975|national final]] to select the first ever Turkish entrant to the Eurovision Song Contest. The final took place on 9 February 1975 in the studios of TRT and was hosted by [[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]]. The winning song, \"[[Seninle Bir Dakika]]\" (literally \"A minute with you\") by [[Semiha Yank\u0131]], was picked by averaging the ranks from the professional jury and people's jury. At the close of voting during the contest, the song received only 3 points from [[Monaco in the Eurovision Song Contest|Monaco]] and placed last.\n\nIn [[Eurovision Song Contest 1976|1976]], Greece's entry to the contest aroused controversy due to its subject matter being the Turkish invasion of Cyprus. Turkey withdrew from the contest to protest the political background of Greece's entry, called \"[[Panagia Mou, Panagia Mou]].\" Turkey televised the final on 3 April 1976 but censored the Greek entrant's performance. They played a nationalist Turkish song titled \"Memleketim\" (literally \"My motherland\", the Turkish cover of the Yiddish folk song \"Rabbi Elimelekh\"), which was one of the symbols of the Turkish invasion of Cyprus in Turkey.\n\nTurkey did not take part in the contest again until [[Eurovision Song Contest 1978|1978]], placing 18th with the song \"[[Sevince]]\" performed by [[Nazar (band)|Nazar]] and [[Nil\u00fcfer Yumlu|Nil\u00fcfer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/paris-1978/final?sorting=rank&direction=asc|title=Final of Paris 1978 |publisher=Eurovision Song Contest |access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Eurovision Song Contest 1979|The 1979 contest]] was held in [[Jerusalem]]. The Turkish entry selected was \"[[Seviyorum]]\" (literally \"I'm in love\") by [[Maria Rita Epik]]. However, Turkey withdrew from the contest due to pressure from neighboring countries to do so, which arose from ongoing controversy regarding the status of Jerusalem.\n\n=== 1980s ===\nTurkey participated in the Eurovision Song Contest consistently throughout the 1980s. In [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]], Turkish superstar [[Ajda Pekkan]] and the song \"[[Pet'r Oil|Petrol]]\" was selected by TRT through a national final. Pekkan placed 15th with 23 points, including the first ever score 12 points received by Turkey, coming from [[Morocco in the Eurovision Song Contest|Morocco]].\n\nTurkey had their best result (until 1997) in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1986|1986 contest]] in [[Bergen]], [[Norway]], when [[Klips ve Onlar]] placed ninth with a total of 53 points. The country scored \"nul points\" twice in the eighties, one in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1983|1983]] (shared with [[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest 1983|Spain]]) and the other one in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]]. Several famous Turkish artists performed for the contest during the 1980s, including Ajda Pekkan, [[Neco (singer)|Neco]], [[Candan Er\u00e7etin]] and [[Mazhar-Fuat-\u00d6zkan|MF\u00d6]].\n\n=== 1990s ===\nThe contest's popularity in Turkey suffered after [[Kayahan]], one of the most famous singers in the country, placed 17th out of 22 participating countries with 21 points. After Kayahan's poor result, Turkey's Eurovision entrants were mostly unknown or amateur singers until [[Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]].\n\n[[\u015eebnem Paker]] represented the country in two consecutive years. The first time being in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]] where she qualified for the final and placed 12th, and the second in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1997|1997]] where she placed third, behind the UK and Ireland, with the song \"[[Dinle]]\" (\"Listen\"), sung in Turkish.\n\nAfter the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest#Rule changes by year|free language rule was re-introduced in 1999]], the first Turkish entry to be partially sung in English was at the {{escyr|2000}} contest. Turkey reached the top 10 for a second time since 1986, and landed in the top three for the first time, making it the most successful result for the country until its victory in 2003. \u015eebnem Paker returned to the [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 1998|Turkish national final]] in 1998, but placed fourth and did not qualify for the Contest as the Turkish participant for a third consecutive year. [[Tarkan T\u00fczmen|T\u00fczmen]] represented the country and placed 14th. Turkey participated all the series of the contest in the 1990s except for [[Eurovision Song Contest 1994|the 1994 contest]], from which they were relegated due to their 21st-place finish in 1993.\n\n=== 2000s and 2010s ===\nIn the late 1990s to early 2000s, the contest became one of the most popular events in Turkey as a result of the participation of other Eastern European countries, and the victory of [[Sertab Erener]] with the song \"[[Everyway That I Can]]\". Following the introduction of [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest#Rule changes by year|televoting in 1998]], (initially trialed in 1997 and first implemented in Turkey in 1999), Turkey went on to achieve eight top 10 results in the contest, having previously made the top 10 in 1986 and 1997.\n\nErener's song for [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]] was the first Turkish entry in the contest to be sung completely in English. TRT selected the Turkish entry through an internal selection mainly organised by [[OGAE|OGAE Turkey]].\n\nThe 2004 contest was held  in the [[Abdi Ipekci Arena]], with the first ever semi-final held on Wednesday 12 May, followed by the final on Saturday 15 May. After Erener's victory (with the exception of the [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]] and [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005]] contest), Turkish entries to the Contest were picked internally. Turkey had always qualified to the grand final (except for [[Eurovision Song Contest 2011|the 2011 Contest]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]]) since introduction of the semi-finals in 2004 and always reached the top ten, except in 2005 and [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2006|2006]], until the last contest they participated in (as of 2018) in 2012. From 2000, Turkey had seven songs sung in English and four sung in both English and Turkish, with just two ({{escyr|2005}} and {{escyr|2008}}) songs sung entirely in Turkish.\n\nAlong with Greece, Turkey brought the contest a new outlook with flashy stage performances and dresses alongside their oriental/Mediterranean-flavoured pop music acts (Sertab Erener, [[Sibel T\u00fcz\u00fcn]], [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] and [[Hadise]]). In 2004, [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]], [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2010|2010]] and [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011]], the country was represented by bands, most being with rock-influenced songs with Ottoman, Eastern European and Balkan instruments. [[Athena (band)|Athena]] ranked fourth in 2004, when the contest was held in Istanbul; [[Mor ve \u00d6tesi]] ranked 7th with a song completely in Turkish in 2008 and the [[nu metal]] band [[Manga (band)|maNga]], which was named the [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best European Act|Best European Act]] in the [[MTV Europe Music Awards 2009]], ranked 2nd in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2010]] respectively. Although [[Y\u00fcksek Sadakat]] in 2011 placed 13th in the first semi-final of the contest and failed to qualify, this was the first and only time that Turkey didn't qualify for the final. In 2012 Turkey participated to the Eurovision Song Contest for the last time as of 2018 with the song \"[[Love Me Back (Can Bonomo song)|Love Me Back]]\" completely sung in English by up-and-coming artist [[Can Bonomo]], which qualified for and placed seventh in the final with 112 points.\n\n==== Withdrawal and controversy ====\nTRT announced their withdrawal from the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013]] on 14 December 2012, citing dissatisfaction with the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest|rules of the competition]]; they have yet to return.<ref name=\"wthdrw1\"/> The TRT cited the changes to the [[Voting at the Eurovision Song Contest|televote voting system]], in which a jury was introduced and the significance of televoting decreased by 50%. Televoting was instated with the purpose of boosting ratings for the Song Contest.<ref>{{cite web|title=T\u00fcrkiye Eurovision'da yok|url=http://www.ntv.com.tr/turkiye/turkiye-eurovisionda-yok,GIEVwyxODEiB-c-QNGPPgQ?_ref=infinite|language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=TRT won't accept the Big 5 and high participation fees|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/08/09/forget-eurovision-journalist-says-turkeys-trt-wont-accept-big-5-high-participation-fees/194442/|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Have Turkey Withdrawn From Eurovision?|url=https://www.eurovoxx.net/single-post/2017/08/10/Why-Have-Turkey-Withdrawn-From-Eurovision?action_object_map=%5B1320901068022222%5D&action_ref_map=%5B%5D&action_type_map=%5B%22og.comments%22%5D&fb_action_ids=10156497794873332&fb_action_types=og.comments&fb_source=other_multiline|language=English}}</ref>\n\nFor the first time, TRT did not televise the 2013 contest, nor did it broadcast the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014 contest]]. Turkey did not participate in any of the contests from 2015 through 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey: TRT confirms no return to Eurovision in 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86670/turkey-trt-confirms-return-eurovision-2015/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|date=5 September 2014|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey: TRT confirms non participation in Eurovision 2016|url=http://esctoday.com/105436/turkey-trt-confirms-non-participation-in-eurovision-2016/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://esctoday.com/149221/turkey-trt-confirms-non-participation-eurovision-2018/|title=Turkey: TRT confirms non participation in Eurovision 2018|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=7 August 2017|work=|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, \u0130brahim Eren, the General Manager of TRT, stated that TRT does not plan to rejoin the contest and break the boycott for various reasons, citing [[Conchita Wurst]]'s representation for [[Austria in the Eurovision Song Contest|Austria]] in {{Escyr|2014}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abcgazetesi.com/guncel/trt-genel-mudurunden-eurovision-aciklamasi/haber-98133|title=TRT Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcr\u00fc'nden Eurovision a\u00e7\u0131klamas\u0131|work=ABC Gazetesi|date=4 August 2018|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey to return Eurovision 'if no more bearded divas' |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-to-return-eurovision-if-no-more-bearded-divas-135427 |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=Hurriyet |date=4 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Contestants==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|width=15px bgcolor=gold|{{center|1}}\n|Winner\n|-\n|bgcolor=silver|{{center|2}}\n|Second place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#c96|{{center|3}}\n|Third place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#FE8080|{{center|\u25c1}}\n|Last place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#A4EAA9|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Language\n!Title\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Final\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Points\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Semi\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Points\n|-bgcolor=\"#FE8080\"\n!{{Escyr|1975}}\n|[[Semiha Yank\u0131]]\n|[[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n|\"[[Seninle Bir Dakika]]\"\n|align=center|19 \u25c1\n|align=center|3\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate in {{ESCYr|1976}} and {{ESCYr|1977}}}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1978}}\n|[[Nil\u00fcfer Yumlu|Nil\u00fcfer]] and Grup Nazar\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Sevince]]\"\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|2\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-bgcolor=\"#A4EAA9\"\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|1979}}}}\n|[[Maria Rita Epik]] and [[21. Peron]]\n|Turkish\n|\"Seviyorum\"\n|colspan=4 {{N/A|Withdrew}}{{efn|name=note1|The 1979 contest was held in the Israeli capital [[Jerusalem]]. Although TRT had selected an entry via a [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 1979|national final]], Turkey ultimately withdrew because Arab countries (one of them, Syria, being its southern neighbour) pressured the Turkish government to withdraw from the contest because of the dispute over the [[Status of Jerusalem]].}} '''X'''\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1980}}\n|[[Ajda Pekkan]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Pet'r Oil]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|23\n|rowspan=\"13\" colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1981}}\n|[[Modern Folk Trio]] and [[Ay\u015feg\u00fcl Aldin\u00e7|Ay\u015feg\u00fcl]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[D\u00f6nme Dolap]]\"\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|9\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1982}}\n|[[Neco (singer)|Neco]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Hani?]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|20\n|-bgcolor=\"#FE8080\"\n!{{Escyr|1983}}\n|[[\u00c7etin Alp]] and The Short Waves\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Opera (song)|Opera]]\"\n|align=center|19 \u25c1\n|align=center|0\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1984}}\n|[[Be\u015f Y\u0131l \u00d6nce, On Y\u0131l Sonra]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Halay (song)|Halay]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|37\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1985}}\n|[[MF\u00d6]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Didai Didai Dai]]\"\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|36\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1986}}\n|[[Klips ve Onlar]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Halley (song)|Halley]]\"\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|53\n|-bgcolor=\"#FE8080\"\n!{{Escyr|1987}}\n|[[Seyyal Taner]] and [[Lokomotif]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[\u015eark\u0131m Sevgi \u00dcst\u00fcne]]\"\n|align=center|22 \u25c1\n|align=center|0\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1988}}\n|[[MF\u00d6]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Sufi (song)|Sufi]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|37\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1989}}\n|[[Pan (Turkish band)|Pan]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Bana Bana]]\"\n|align=center|21\n|align=center|5\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1990}}\n|[[Kayahan]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[G\u00f6zlerinin Hapsindeyim]]\"\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|21\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1991}}\n|[[\u0130zel (singer)|\u0130zel]], [[Reyhan Karaca|Reyhan]] and [[Can U\u011furluel|Can]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[\u0130ki Dakika]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|44\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1992}}\n|[[Aylin Vatanko\u015f]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Yaz Bitti]]\"\n|align=center|19\n|align=center|17\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1993}}\n|[[Burak Aydos]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Esmer Yarim]]\"\n|align=center|21\n|align=center|10\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|[[Kvalifikacija za Millstreet]]}}\n|-\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|1994}}}}\n|colspan=\"7\" {{N/A|Did not participate}} \n|-\n!{{Escyr|1995}}\n|[[Arzu Ece]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Sev (song)|Sev]]\"\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|21\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1996}}\n|[[\u015eebnem Paker]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Be\u015finci Mevsim]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|57\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|69\n|-bgcolor=\"#cc9966\"\n!{{Escyr|1997}}\n|[[\u015eebnem Paker]] and [[Grup Etnik]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Dinle]]\"\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|121\n|rowspan=\"7\" colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1998}}\n|[[Tarkan T\u00fczmen|T\u00fczmen]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Unutamazs\u0131n]]\"\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|25\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1999}}\n|[[Tuba \u00d6nal]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[D\u00f6n Art\u0131k]]\"\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|21\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2000}}\n|[[P\u0131nar Ayhan]] and [[Grup SOS]]\n|Turkish, [[English language|English]]\n|\"[[Yorgunum Anla]]\"\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|59\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2001}}\n|[[Sedat Y\u00fcce]]\n|Turkish, English\n|\"[[Sevgiliye Son]]\"\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|41\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2002}}\n|[[Buket Bengisu]]\n|Turkish, English\n|\"[[Leylaklar Soldu Kalbinde]]\"\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|29\n|-bgcolor=\"gold\"\n!{{Escyr|2003}}\n|[[Sertab Erener]]\n|English\n|\"[[Everyway That I Can]]\"\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|167\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2004}}\n|[[Athena (band)|Athena]]\n|English\n|\"[[For Real (Athena song)|For Real]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|195\n|colspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"-9999\" {{N/A|Host country}}{{efn|name=note3|If a country had won the previous year, they did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year.}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2005}}\n|[[G\u00fclseren]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Rimi Rimi Ley]]\"\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|92\n|colspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"-9999\" {{N/A|Top 12 Previous Year}}{{efn|name=note4|According to the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest|then-Eurovision rules]], the top ten non-[[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big Four]] countries from the previous year along with the Big Four automatically qualified for the Grand Final without having to compete in semi-finals. For example, if Germany and France placed inside the top ten, the 11th and 12th spots were advanced to next year's Grand Final along with all countries ranked in the top ten.}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2006}}\n|[[Sibel T\u00fcz\u00fcn]]\n|Turkish, English\n|\"[[Superstar (Sibel T\u00fcz\u00fcn song)|Superstar]]\"\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|91\n|align=center|8\n|align=center|91\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2007}}\n|[[Kenan Do\u011fulu]]\n|English\n|\"[[Shake It Up \u015eekerim]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|163\n|bgcolor=\"#cc9966\" align=center|3\n|bgcolor=\"#cc9966\" align=center|197\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2008}}\n|[[Mor ve \u00d6tesi]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Deli (song)|Deli]]\"\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|138\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|85\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2009}}\n|[[Hadise]]\n|English\n|\"[[D\u00fcm Tek Tek]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|177\n|bgcolor = \"silver\" align=center|2\n|bgcolor = \"silver\" align=center|172\n|-bgcolor = \"silver\"\n!{{Escyr|2010}}\n|[[Manga (band)|maNga]]\n|English\n|\"[[We Could Be the Same]]\"\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|170\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" align=center|1\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" align=center|118\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2011}}\n|[[Y\u00fcksek Sadakat]]\n|English\n|\"[[Live It Up (Y\u00fcksek Sadakat song)|Live It Up]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|47\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2012}}\n|[[Can Bonomo]]\n|English\n|\"[[Love Me Back (Can Bonomo song)|Love Me Back]]\"\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|112\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|80\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\" {{N/A|Did not participate from {{Escyr|2013}} to {{Escyr|2020}}}}\n|}\n;<small>'''Notes:'''</small>\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest===\n{{further2|[[Congratulations (Eurovision)|Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest]]}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Artist\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Language\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!colspan=\"4\"|At Congratulations\n!colspan=\"3\"|At Eurovision\n|-\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Final\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points \n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Semi\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Year\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Place\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Sertab Erener]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[English language|English]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Everyway That I Can]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|9\n|104\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|{{Escyr|2003}}\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|1\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|167\n|}\n\n==Hostings==\n<!-- DO NOT add flagicons to the host city column.  This article is already about Turkey, so there is no need to highlight with {{flagicon}} that the city is in Turkey. This is in accordance with [[WP:ICONDECORATION]]. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n!Year\n!Location\n!Venue\n!Presenters\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|[[Istanbul]]\n|[[Abdi \u0130pek\u00e7i Arena]]\n|[[Korhan Abay]] and [[Meltem Cumbul]]\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n===Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards===\n{{further|Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Category\n!Song\n!Performer\n!style=\"width:45px;\"|Final\n!style=\"width:45px;\"|Points\n!Host city\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{escyr|2003}}\n|Press Award\n| \"[[Everyway That I Can]]\"\n| [[Sertab Erener]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|167\n|{{flagicon|Latvia}} [[Riga]]\n|}\n\n==Commentators and spokespersons==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2012}}\n\nPrior to 2012 every contest Turkey had taken part in had always been commentated on by Turkish television presenter [[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]], with the exception of 1982\u20131985, 1990\u20131991, 1998\u20132001 and 2007. In addition \u00d6zveren also co-commentated the contest in 1979, 2004, 2011 and 2012. Out of the 38 years Turkey have broadcast the event \u00d6zveren has commentated on 29 of them making him 9 years short of being the contest's longest commentator.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Commentator\n!Spokesperson\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1973}}\n|rowspan=\"9\"|[[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]] ||rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1974}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1975}}\n|B\u00fclent Osma ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1976}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1977}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1978}}\n|Meral Savc\u0131 ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1979}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1980}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Ba\u015fak Do\u011fru ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1981}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1982}}\n|[[\u00dcmit Tun\u00e7a\u011f]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1983}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Ba\u015fak Do\u011fru]] ||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Fatih Orbay]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1984}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1985}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1986}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|G\u00fclg\u00fcn Feyman ||\u00dcmit Tun\u00e7a\u011f ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1987}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Canan Kumbasar ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1988}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1989}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1990}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Ba\u015fak Do\u011fru ||Korhan Abay ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1991}}\n|Canan Kumbasar ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1992}}\n|rowspan=\"6\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||Korhan Abay ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1993}}\n|[[\u00d6mer \u00d6nder]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1994}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1995}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|\u00d6mer \u00d6nder ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1996}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1997}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1998}}\n|\u00d6mer \u00d6nder || rowspan=\"3\" |Osman Erkan ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1999}}\n|G\u00fcl\u015fah Banda ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2000}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u00d6mer \u00d6nder ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2001}}\n|rowspan=\"10\"|Meltem Ersan Yazgan ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2002}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2003}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|Didem Tolunay and B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren  ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2005}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2006}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007}}\n|Hakan Urganc\u0131  ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren and Erhan Konuk || rowspan=\"2\" |\u00d6mer \u00d6nder ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\u2013{{Escyr|2019}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}||{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|}\n\n==Photogallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:Eurovision 2004 Opening Ceremony Sertab Erener.jpg|[[Sertab Erener]] in the opening of [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|the 2004 Contest]].\nImage:ESC 2007 Turkey - Kenan Do\u011fulu - Shake it up Shekerim.jpg|[[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] at Helsinki ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]])\nImage:Mor ve \u00d6tesi, Turkey, ESC 2008, 2nd semifinal.jpg|[[Mor ve \u00d6tesi]] at Belgrade ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]])\nImage:Hadise.jpg|[[Hadise]] at Moscow ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]])\nImage:MaNga - We Could be the Same (2nd Semi-final).jpg|[[Manga (band)|maNga]] at Oslo ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2010|2010]])\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Music of Turkey]]\n* [[Turkey in the ABU TV Song Festival]]\n* [[Turkey in the Bala Turkvision Song Contest]]\n* [[Turkey in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n* [[Turkey in the Turkvision Song Contest]]\n* [[Turkish pop music]]\n* [[Turks in Europe]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070527023155/http://www.eurosong.net/songs/list.php?country=tr Lyrics of all Turkish Eurovision entries]\n*[http://www.eurovisioncovers.co.uk/xttur.htm Points to and from Turkey] ''eurovisioncovers.co.uk''\n\n{{Turkey in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turkey In The Eurovision Song Contest}}\n[[Category:Countries in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name = Turkey\n| Member station = [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation]] (TRT)\n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title = National final\n | 1975\n | 1978\n | 1980\u20131993\n | 1995\u20132002\n | 2004\u20132005\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title = Internal selection\n | 2003\n | 2006\u20132012\n}}\n| ESC apps = 34 (33 finals)\n| ESC first = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975]]\n| ESC last = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]]\n| ESC best = 1st: [[Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]]\n| ESC worst = Last: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1983|1983]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]]\n| Nul points = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1983|1983]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]]\n| Website = [http://www.trteurovision.eu TRT page]\n| EBU page = https://eurovision.tv/country/turkey\n| Current = 2012\n}}\n\n'''Turkey''' has participated in the '''[[Eurovision Song Contest]]''' 34 times since [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975]]. Since the introduction of the semi-finals in {{escyr|2004}}, the only year that Turkey participated and failed to advance to the finals was in {{escyr|2011}}. Turkey won the contest once in {{escyr|2003}}, and hosted the {{escyr|2004}} contest in [[Istanbul]].\n\nTurkey finished last on its debut at the contest in 1975, and went on to finish last with \"[[nul points]]\" in {{escyr|1983}} and {{escyr|1987}}. They reached the top ten for the first time in 1986. [[\u015eebnem Paker]] achieved the country's first top five result in {{escyr|1997}}, finishing third with the song \"[[Dinle]]\".\n\nThey went on to achieve five more top five placements after the introduction of the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest#Rule changes by year|free language rule]] and televoting, with [[Sertab Erener]] giving Turkey its first victory in {{escyr|2003}} with the song \"[[Everyway That I Can]]\", narrowly defeating [[Belgium in the Eurovision Song Contest|Belgium]] by two points. Turkey's other top five results are [[Athena (band)|Athena]] ({{escyr|2004}}), [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] ({{escyr|2007}}), [[Hadise]] ({{escyr|2009}}), who all finished fourth, and the [[nu metal]] band [[maNga (band)|maNga]] ({{escyr|2010}}), who finished second.\n\nThe [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]] announced in December 2012 that they would not attend the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013 contest]] in [[Malm\u00f6]], citing dissatisfaction with the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest|rules of the competition]].<ref name=\"wthdrw1\">{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey will not go to Eurovision in Malm\u00f6|url=http://www.esctoday.com/40037/turkey-will-not-be-in-malmo/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=14 December 2012|date=14 December 2012}}</ref> 2013 was the first time since {{escyr|1973}} that there was no television broadcast of the Eurovision Song Contest on TRT. In September 2013, TRT stated a return is unlikely for [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|the 2014 competition]], citing the same reasons.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey: TRT will not participate in Eurovision 2014|url=http://www.esctoday.com/68587/turkey-trt-will-not-participate-in-eurovision-2014/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=7 November 2013|date=7 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"nobroadcast\">{{cite web|title=TRT, Eurovision'u yay\u0131nlamaktan vazge\u00e7ti!|url=https://www.ogunhaber.com/magazin/trt-eurovisionu-yayinlamaktan-vazgecti-145790h.html}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Turkish Radio and Television Corporation involvement in the Eurovision Song Contest ===\nThe national broadcasting service of [[Turkey]], the [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation]] (TRT), was one of the charter members of the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) in 1950 along with eighteen countries around Europe, including [[Tunisia]]. As an intercontinental country (with lands in [[Eastern Thrace]] and [[Western Asia]]), Turkey takes part in a multitude of Western organizations including [[NATO]] as of 1952 and the [[European Economic Community]] as an [[Member State of the European Union#Related states|associate member]] as of 1959.\n\nTRT televised the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] between [[Eurovision Song Contest 1973|1973]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]], even during years in which Turkey was not participating in the contest.\n\n=== 1970s ===\nTurkey participated in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975 Eurovision Song Contest]] held in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]. [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest|Greece]] did not take part in the 1975 Contest for \"unknown reasons\" according to the [[European Broadcasting Union|EBU]], but it was later revealed that the withdrawal was in protest of Turkey's debut and their [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|invasion of Cyprus]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ogaegreece.com/node/150|title=EUROVISION SONG CONTEST 1975|publisher=OGAE Greece|language=Greek|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Raycoff|first=Ivan|author2=Robert Deayom Tobin|title=A Song for Europe|date=July 2007|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing]]|isbn= 978-0-7546-5878-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Eq7nilnv93cC&printsec=frontcover&dq=a+song+for+europe&client=firefox-a&sig=ACfU3U0r2r9IklIU3MfJf6wIZOWTlbgE4A#PPR18,M1|location=[[Aldershot]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]]}}</ref> TRT organized a [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 1975|national final]] to select the first ever Turkish entrant to the Eurovision Song Contest. The final took place on 9 February 1975 in the studios of TRT and was hosted by [[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]]. The winning song, \"[[Seninle Bir Dakika]]\" (literally \"A minute with you\") by [[Semiha Yank\u0131]], was picked by averaging the ranks from the professional jury and people's jury. At the close of voting during the contest, the song received only 3 points from [[Monaco in the Eurovision Song Contest|Monaco]] and placed last.\n\nIn [[Eurovision Song Contest 1976|1976]], Greece's entry to the contest aroused controversy due to its subject matter being the Turkish invasion of Cyprus. Turkey withdrew from the contest to protest the political background of Greece's entry, called \"[[Panagia Mou, Panagia Mou]].\" Turkey televised the final on 3 April 1976 but censored the Greek entrant's performance. They played a nationalist Turkish song titled \"Memleketim\" (literally \"My motherland\", the Turkish cover of the Yiddish folk song \"Rabbi Elimelekh\"), which was one of the symbols of the Turkish invasion of Cyprus in Turkey.\n\nTurkey did not take part in the contest again until [[Eurovision Song Contest 1978|1978]], placing 18th with the song \"[[Sevince]]\" performed by [[Nazar (band)|Nazar]] and [[Nil\u00fcfer Yumlu|Nil\u00fcfer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/paris-1978/final?sorting=rank&direction=asc|title=Final of Paris 1978 |publisher=Eurovision Song Contest |access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Eurovision Song Contest 1979|The 1979 contest]] was held in [[Jerusalem]]. The Turkish entry selected was \"[[Seviyorum]]\" (literally \"I'm in love\") by [[Maria Rita Epik]]. However, Turkey withdrew from the contest due to pressure from neighboring countries to do so, which arose from ongoing controversy regarding the status of Jerusalem.\n\n=== 1980s ===\nTurkey participated in the Eurovision Song Contest consistently throughout the 1980s. In [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]], Turkish superstar [[Ajda Pekkan]] and the song \"[[Pet'r Oil|Petrol]]\" was selected by TRT through a national final. Pekkan placed 15th with 23 points, including the first ever score 12 points received by Turkey, coming from [[Morocco in the Eurovision Song Contest|Morocco]].\n\nTurkey had their best result (until 1997) in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1986|1986 contest]] in [[Bergen]], [[Norway]], when [[Klips ve Onlar]] placed ninth with a total of 53 points. The country scored \"nul points\" twice in the eighties, one in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1983|1983]] (shared with [[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest 1983|Spain]]) and the other one in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]]. Several famous Turkish artists performed for the contest during the 1980s, including Ajda Pekkan, [[Neco (singer)|Neco]], [[Candan Er\u00e7etin]] and [[Mazhar-Fuat-\u00d6zkan|MF\u00d6]].\n\n=== 1990s ===\nThe contest's popularity in Turkey suffered after [[Kayahan]], one of the most famous singers in the country, placed 17th out of 22 participating countries with 21 points. After Kayahan's poor result, Turkey's Eurovision entrants were mostly unknown or amateur singers until [[Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]].\n\n[[\u015eebnem Paker]] represented the country in two consecutive years. The first time being in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]] where she qualified for the final and placed 12th, and the second in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1997|1997]] where she placed third, behind the UK and Ireland, with the song \"[[Dinle]]\" (\"Listen\"), sung in Turkish.\n\nAfter the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest#Rule changes by year|free language rule was re-introduced in 1999]], the first Turkish entry to be partially sung in English was at the {{escyr|2000}} contest. Turkey reached the top 10 for a second time since 1986, and landed in the top three for the first time, making it the most successful result for the country until its victory in 2003. \u015eebnem Paker returned to the [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 1998|Turkish national final]] in 1998, but placed fourth and did not qualify for the Contest as the Turkish participant for a third consecutive year. [[Tarkan T\u00fczmen|T\u00fczmen]] represented the country and placed 14th. Turkey participated all the series of the contest in the 1990s except for [[Eurovision Song Contest 1994|the 1994 contest]], from which they were relegated due to their 21st-place finish in 1993.\n\n=== 2000s and 2010s ===\nIn the late 1990s to early 2000s, the contest became one of the most popular events in Turkey as a result of the participation of other Eastern European countries, and the victory of [[Sertab Erener]] with the song \"[[Everyway That I Can]]\". Following the introduction of [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest#Rule changes by year|televoting in 1998]], (initially trialed in 1997 and first implemented in Turkey in 1999), Turkey went on to achieve eight top 10 results in the contest, having previously made the top 10 in 1986 and 1997.\n\nErener's song for [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]] was the first Turkish entry in the contest to be sung completely in English. TRT selected the Turkish entry through an internal selection mainly organised by [[OGAE|OGAE Turkey]].\n\nThe 2004 contest was held  in the [[Abdi Ipekci Arena]], with the first ever semi-final held on Wednesday 12 May, followed by the final on Saturday 15 May. After Erener's victory (with the exception of the [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]] and [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005]] contest), Turkish entries to the Contest were picked internally. Turkey had always qualified to the grand final (except for [[Eurovision Song Contest 2011|the 2011 Contest]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]]) since introduction of the semi-finals in 2004 and always reached the top ten, except in 2005 and [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2006|2006]], until the last contest they participated in (as of 2018) in 2012. From 2000, Turkey had seven songs sung in English and four sung in both English and Turkish, with just two ({{escyr|2005}} and {{escyr|2008}}) songs sung entirely in Turkish.\n\nAlong with Greece, Turkey brought the contest a new outlook with flashy stage performances and dresses alongside their oriental/Mediterranean-flavoured pop music acts (Sertab Erener, [[Sibel T\u00fcz\u00fcn]], [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] and [[Hadise]]). In 2004, [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]], [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2010|2010]] and [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011]], the country was represented by bands, most being with rock-influenced songs with Ottoman, Eastern European and Balkan instruments. [[Athena (band)|Athena]] ranked fourth in 2004, when the contest was held in Istanbul; [[Mor ve \u00d6tesi]] ranked 7th with a song completely in Turkish in 2008 and the [[nu metal]] band [[Manga (band)|maNga]], which was named the [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best European Act|Best European Act]] in the [[MTV Europe Music Awards 2009]], ranked 2nd in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2010]] respectively. Although [[Y\u00fcksek Sadakat]] in 2011 placed 13th in the first semi-final of the contest and failed to qualify, this was the first and only time that Turkey didn't qualify for the final. In 2012 Turkey participated to the Eurovision Song Contest for the last time as of 2018 with the song \"[[Love Me Back (Can Bonomo song)|Love Me Back]]\" completely sung in English by up-and-coming artist [[Can Bonomo]], which qualified for and placed seventh in the final with 112 points.\n\n==== Withdrawal and controversy ====\nTRT announced their withdrawal from the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013]] on 14 December 2012, citing dissatisfaction with the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest|rules of the competition]]; they have yet to return.<ref name=\"wthdrw1\"/> The TRT cited the changes to the [[Voting at the Eurovision Song Contest|televote voting system]], in which a jury was introduced and the significance of televoting decreased by 50%. Televoting was instated with the purpose of boosting ratings for the Song Contest.<ref>{{cite web|title=T\u00fcrkiye Eurovision'da yok|url=http://www.ntv.com.tr/turkiye/turkiye-eurovisionda-yok,GIEVwyxODEiB-c-QNGPPgQ?_ref=infinite|language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=TRT won't accept the Big 5 and high participation fees|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/08/09/forget-eurovision-journalist-says-turkeys-trt-wont-accept-big-5-high-participation-fees/194442/|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Have Turkey Withdrawn From Eurovision?|url=https://www.eurovoxx.net/single-post/2017/08/10/Why-Have-Turkey-Withdrawn-From-Eurovision?action_object_map=%5B1320901068022222%5D&action_ref_map=%5B%5D&action_type_map=%5B%22og.comments%22%5D&fb_action_ids=10156497794873332&fb_action_types=og.comments&fb_source=other_multiline|language=English}}</ref>\n\nFor the first time, TRT did not televise the 2013 contest, nor did it broadcast the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014 contest]]. Turkey did not participate in any of the contests from 2015 through 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey: TRT confirms no return to Eurovision in 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86670/turkey-trt-confirms-return-eurovision-2015/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|date=5 September 2014|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Turkey: TRT confirms non participation in Eurovision 2016|url=http://esctoday.com/105436/turkey-trt-confirms-non-participation-in-eurovision-2016/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://esctoday.com/149221/turkey-trt-confirms-non-participation-eurovision-2018/|title=Turkey: TRT confirms non participation in Eurovision 2018|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=7 August 2017|work=|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, \u0130brahim Eren, the General Manager of TRT, stated that TRT does not plan to rejoin the contest and break the boycott for various reasons, citing [[Conchita Wurst]]'s representation for [[Austria in the Eurovision Song Contest|Austria]] in {{Escyr|2014}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abcgazetesi.com/guncel/trt-genel-mudurunden-eurovision-aciklamasi/haber-98133|title=TRT Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcr\u00fc'nden Eurovision a\u00e7\u0131klamas\u0131|work=ABC Gazetesi|date=4 August 2018|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey to return Eurovision 'if no more bearded divas' |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-to-return-eurovision-if-no-more-bearded-divas-135427 |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=Hurriyet |date=4 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Contestants==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|width=15px bgcolor=gold|{{center|1}}\n|Winner\n|-\n|bgcolor=silver|{{center|2}}\n|Second place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#c96|{{center|3}}\n|Third place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#FE8080|{{center|\u25c1}}\n|Last place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#A4EAA9|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Language\n!Title\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Final\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Points\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Semi\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" width=50px|Points\n|-bgcolor=\"#FE8080\"\n!{{Escyr|1975}}\n|[[Semiha Yank\u0131]]\n|[[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n|\"[[Seninle Bir Dakika]]\"\n|align=center|19 \u25c1\n|align=center|3\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate in {{ESCYr|1976}} and {{ESCYr|1977}}}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1978}}\n|[[Nil\u00fcfer Yumlu|Nil\u00fcfer]] and Grup Nazar\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Sevince]]\"\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|2\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-bgcolor=\"#A4EAA9\"\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|1979}}}}\n|[[Maria Rita Epik]] and [[21. Peron]]\n|Turkish\n|\"Seviyorum\"\n|colspan=4 {{N/A|Withdrew{{efn|name=note1|The 1979 contest was held in the Israeli capital [[Jerusalem]]. Although TRT had selected an entry via a [[Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest 1979|national final]], Turkey ultimately withdrew because Arab countries (one of them, Syria, being its southern neighbour) pressured the Turkish government to withdraw from the contest because of the dispute over the [[Status of Jerusalem]].}}}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1980}}\n|[[Ajda Pekkan]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Pet'r Oil]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|23\n|rowspan=\"13\" colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1981}}\n|[[Modern Folk Trio]] and [[Ay\u015feg\u00fcl Aldin\u00e7|Ay\u015feg\u00fcl]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[D\u00f6nme Dolap]]\"\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|9\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1982}}\n|[[Neco (singer)|Neco]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Hani?]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|20\n|-bgcolor=\"#FE8080\"\n!{{Escyr|1983}}\n|[[\u00c7etin Alp]] and The Short Waves\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Opera (song)|Opera]]\"\n|align=center|19 \u25c1\n|align=center|0\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1984}}\n|[[Be\u015f Y\u0131l \u00d6nce, On Y\u0131l Sonra]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Halay (song)|Halay]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|37\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1985}}\n|[[MF\u00d6]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Didai Didai Dai]]\"\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|36\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1986}}\n|[[Klips ve Onlar]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Halley (song)|Halley]]\"\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|53\n|-bgcolor=\"#FE8080\"\n!{{Escyr|1987}}\n|[[Seyyal Taner]] and [[Lokomotif]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[\u015eark\u0131m Sevgi \u00dcst\u00fcne]]\"\n|align=center|22 \u25c1\n|align=center|0\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1988}}\n|[[MF\u00d6]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Sufi (song)|Sufi]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|37\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1989}}\n|[[Pan (Turkish band)|Pan]]\n|Turkish\n|\"[[Bana Bana]]\"\n|align=center|21\n|align=center|5\n|-\n!{