 Up]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|47\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2012}}\n|[[Can Bonomo]]\n|English\n|\"[[Love Me Back (Can Bonomo song)|Love Me Back]]\"\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|112\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|80\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\" {{N/A|Did not participate from {{Escyr|2013}} to {{Escyr|2020}}}}\n|}\n;<small>'''Notes:'''</small>\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest===\n{{further2|[[Congratulations (Eurovision)|Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest]]}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Artist\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Language\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!colspan=\"4\"|At Congratulations\n!colspan=\"3\"|At Eurovision\n|-\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Final\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points \n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Semi\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Year\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Place\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Sertab Erener]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[English language|English]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Everyway That I Can]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|9\n|104\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|{{Escyr|2003}}\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|1\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|167\n|}\n\n==Hostings==\n<!-- DO NOT add flagicons to the host city column.  This article is already about Turkey, so there is no need to highlight with {{flagicon}} that the city is in Turkey. This is in accordance with [[WP:ICONDECORATION]]. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n!Year\n!Location\n!Venue\n!Presenters\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|[[Istanbul]]\n|[[Abdi \u0130pek\u00e7i Arena]]\n|[[Korhan Abay]] and [[Meltem Cumbul]]\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n===Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards===\n{{further|Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Category\n!Song\n!Performer\n!style=\"width:45px;\"|Final\n!style=\"width:45px;\"|Points\n!Host city\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{escyr|2003}}\n|Press Award\n| \"[[Everyway That I Can]]\"\n| [[Sertab Erener]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|167\n|{{flagicon|Latvia}} [[Riga]]\n|}\n\n==Commentators and spokespersons==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2012}}\n\nPrior to 2012 every contest Turkey had taken part in had always been commentated on by Turkish television presenter [[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]], with the exception of 1982\u20131985, 1990\u20131991, 1998\u20132001 and 2007. In addition \u00d6zveren also co-commentated the contest in 1979, 2004, 2011 and 2012. Out of the 38 years Turkey have broadcast the event \u00d6zveren has commentated on 29 of them making him 9 years short of being the contest's longest commentator.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Commentator\n!Spokesperson\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1973}}\n|rowspan=\"9\"|[[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]] ||rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1974}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1975}}\n|B\u00fclent Osma ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1976}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1977}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1978}}\n|Meral Savc\u0131 ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1979}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1980}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Ba\u015fak Do\u011fru ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1981}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1982}}\n|[[\u00dcmit Tun\u00e7a\u011f]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1983}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Ba\u015fak Do\u011fru]] ||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Fatih Orbay]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1984}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1985}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1986}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|G\u00fclg\u00fcn Feyman ||\u00dcmit Tun\u00e7a\u011f ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1987}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Canan Kumbasar ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1988}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1989}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1990}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Ba\u015fak Do\u011fru ||Korhan Abay ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1991}}\n|Canan Kumbasar ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1992}}\n|rowspan=\"6\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||Korhan Abay ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1993}}\n|[[\u00d6mer \u00d6nder]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1994}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1995}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|\u00d6mer \u00d6nder ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1996}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1997}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1998}}\n|\u00d6mer \u00d6nder || rowspan=\"3\" |Osman Erkan ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1999}}\n|G\u00fcl\u015fah Banda ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2000}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u00d6mer \u00d6nder ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2001}}\n|rowspan=\"10\"|Meltem Ersan Yazgan ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2002}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2003}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|Didem Tolunay and B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren  ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2005}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2006}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007}}\n|Hakan Urganc\u0131  ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren and Erhan Konuk || rowspan=\"2\" |\u00d6mer \u00d6nder ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\u2013{{Escyr|2019}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}||{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|}\n\n==Photogallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:Eurovision 2004 Opening Ceremony Sertab Erener.jpg|[[Sertab Erener]] in the opening of [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|the 2004 Contest]].\nImage:ESC 2007 Turkey - Kenan Do\u011fulu - Shake it up Shekerim.jpg|[[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] at Helsinki ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]])\nImage:Mor ve \u00d6tesi, Turkey, ESC 2008, 2nd semifinal.jpg|[[Mor ve \u00d6tesi]] at Belgrade ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]])\nImage:Hadise.jpg|[[Hadise]] at Moscow ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]])\nImage:MaNga - We Could be the Same (2nd Semi-final).jpg|[[Manga (band)|maNga]] at Oslo ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2010|2010]])\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Music of Turkey]]\n* [[Turkey in the ABU TV Song Festival]]\n* [[Turkey in the Bala Turkvision Song Contest]]\n* [[Turkey in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n* [[Turkey in the Turkvision Song Contest]]\n* [[Turkish pop music]]\n* [[Turks in Europe]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070527023155/http://www.eurosong.net/songs/list.php?country=tr Lyrics of all Turkish Eurovision entries]\n*[http://www.eurovisioncovers.co.uk/xttur.htm Points to and from Turkey] ''eurovisioncovers.co.uk''\n\n{{Turkey in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turkey In The Eurovision Song Contest}}\n[[Category:Countries in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:Turkey in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dummelaksen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eContestants", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkey_in_the_Eurovision_Song_Contest"}
{"title_page": "Salem-Keizer Volcanoes", "text_new": "{{More citations needed section|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name            = Salem-Keizer Volcanoes \n|founded         = 1997 \n|city            = Keizer, Oregon \n|misc            =\n|logo            = SalemKeizerVolcanoesLogo.PNG\n|uniformlogo     = SalemKeizerVolcanoesCapLogo.PNG\n|class level     = Short-Season A (1997\u2013present)\n|past class level=\n|current league  = [[Northwest League]] (1997\u2013present)\n|conference      =\n|division        = Southern Division\n|past league     =\n|majorleague     = [[San Francisco Giants]] (1997\u2013present)\n|pastmajorleague =\n|nickname        = Salem-Keizer Volcanoes (1997\u2013present)\n|pastnames       =\n|mascot          = Crater (1997-present)\n|ballpark        = [[Volcanoes Stadium]] (1997\u2013present)\n|pastparks       =\n|leaguenum       = 5\n|leaguechamps    = {{hlist|1998|2001|2006|2007|2009}}\n|divnum          = 7\n|divisionchamps  = {{hlist|1998|2001|2003|2006|2007|2008|2009}}\n|owner           = Jerry Walker<ref>{{cite web |title=Salem-Keizer Volcanoes Staff Directory |url=https://www.milb.com/salem-keizer/about/staff-directory |website=MiLB.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|manager         = [[Lenn Sakata]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Salem-Keizer Volcanoes Roster |url=http://www.milb.com/roster/index.jsp?sid=t578 |website=MiLB.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|gm              =\n|colors= Gray, lava red, obsidian, burnt gold, white<BR/>{{color box|#536878}} {{color box|red}} {{color box|#000}} {{color box|#CC5500}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}}}\nThe '''Salem-Keizer Volcanoes''' are a [[minor league baseball]] team in [[Keizer, Oregon|Keizer]], [[Oregon]], [[United States]]. They are a Short-Season Class A team in the [[Northwest League]], and have been an affiliate of the [[San Francisco Giants]] since the Volcanoes' inception in 1997. They play their home games at [[Volcanoes Stadium]], which opened in 1997 and seats 4,252 fans.\n\n==Baseball in the Salem Area==\nThe Salem-Keizer area has been home to professional baseball since 1940, when the [[Salem Senators]]  (an homage to Salem's role as Oregon's capital) were formed as a member of the Western International League (WIL). When the WIL reformed into the current Northwest League (NWL) in 1955, the Senators were a charter member of the new circuit. The Salem franchise played as the Senators until 1960, when it became a Class A affiliate of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] and adopted the parent club's nickname. The Salem Dodgers continued to play until the 1965 season, after which   the franchise was dormant for 17 years.\n\nIn 1977, former [[Stockton Ports]] owner/manager [[Carl W. Thompson Sr.|Carl Thompson]] purchased the Salem franchise and put it back on the field as an NWL member and Dodgers farm club. The revived Senators played until after the 1981 season, when the [[California Angels]] became the team's parent club.\n\nThe '82 Angels captured the first NWL championship by a Salem-area franchise, and became the first NWL champion with a losing regular-season record, a distinction which lasted until 2005.\n\nThe Salem Angels shifted their major-league affiliation and nickname back to the Dodgers after the 1987 season. The Dodgers played in Salem for two seasons, with future major-league star [[Mike Piazza]] on the team's 1989 roster.\n\nIn 1990, owners moved the Salem Dodgers to [[Yakima, Washington]], mainly due to lack of adequate facilities. The Salem club had played its home games at the [[Chemeketa Community College]] field, which lacked a grandstand, permanent concession stands and other amenities. It would be seven years before pro baseball returned to the Salem-Keizer metropolitan area.\n\n==Reborn as the Volcanoes==\nIn 1996, [[Bellingham Mariners|Bellingham Giants]] co-owners Jerry Walker and William Tucker announced that they were moving the NWL franchise to [[Keizer, Oregon]], a city of 22,000 located immediately north of Salem. The Bellingham club, short-season Class A affiliate of the [[San Francisco Giants]], had the NWL's lowest attendance figures during each of its two seasons.  The move devastated Bellingham baseball fans, many of whom still harbor hard feelings for the entire Giants organization in general and the Volcanoes in particular.\n\nKeizer had striven to assert itself as an independent, thriving city for 12 years since the former Salem suburb had become an incorporated municipality. City officials, led by Mayor Dennis Koho, and civic leaders worked toward getting a new baseball stadium located and built in Keizer. The area had lacked a suitable facility for pro baseball since the early 1960s, when the Salem Dodgers vacated historic Waters Field (which burned down in 1966).\n\nVolcanoes Stadium was built in less than a year, on a tract of land adjacent to [[Interstate 5 in Oregon|Interstate 5]] just northwest of the Keizer interchange. The 4,252-seat facility was ready for the debut of the Salem-Keizer Volcanoes in 1997. Two years later, the American Institute of Architects honored the Volcanoes with a design award for the stadium.\n\nVolcanoes Stadium also hosts all five of [[Oregon Schools Activities Association|Oregon's state high school baseball]] championship games. In 1998, the [[University of Oregon]] [[1998 Oregon Ducks football team|football team]] played its spring Green-White game in the stadium in early May.<ref name=strshn>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3UxWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6usDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1908%2C1104766 |work=Eugene Register-Guard  |last=Clark |first=Bob |title=UO starters shine against the reserves |date=May 3, 1998 |page=1G}}</ref>\n\nArea fans chose the nickname \"Volcanoes\" in a contest. The new franchise was designated as a \"Salem-Keizer\" team, despite its location, in order to incorporate both the history and the prestige of the larger city and state capital.\n\nAs of 2009, the Volcanoes have won seven Western Division titles, including four straight between 2006 and 2009. The others came in the 1998, 2001 and 2003 seasons.\n\nSalem-Keizer has won five NWL championships, in 1998, 2001, 2006, 2007, and 2009.\n\nIn 2001, the Volcanoes won the Freitas Award as the best short-season Class A baseball franchise in the U.S.\n\nNotable former Salem-Keizer Volcanoes include [[Brian Horwitz]], [[Joe Nathan]], [[Ryan Vogelsong]], [[Pablo Sandoval]], [[Kurt Ainsworth]], [[Jesse Foppert]], [[Travis Ishikawa]], [[Noah Lowry]], [[Tim Lincecum]], [[Buster Posey]], and [[Lance Niekro]]. Since 1997, 84 former Volcanoes have played in the major leagues.\n\nTwo former Volcanoes also played in the inaugural [[2006 in baseball|2006]] [[World Baseball Classic]]: [[Joe Nathan]] (U.S.) and [[Jonathan S\u00e1nchez]] (Puerto Rico).\n\n===2006 Season===\n[[File:Volcanoes Stadium Keizer Oregon wide.JPG|thumb|Volcanoes Stadium]]\nThe Volcanoes celebrated their 10th season in Salem-Keizer by ending the regular season with an NWL-record 55 victories. (The record is for the years since the league adopted a 76-game regular season.) The Volcanoes led the NWL in many categories during 2006, and set franchise records of:\n\n* Most consecutive games won (12)\n* Most runs in an inning (10), in the seventh inning of a 19-3 rout of the [[Vancouver Canadians|Canadians]] on August 30. In that game, catcher Adam Witter hitting the team's first ever [[Hitting for the cycle|cycle]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.minorleaguebaseball.com/app/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060830&content_id=125814&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp\n| title = Volcanoes' Witter hits for cycle {{hyphen}} Catcher caps feat with homer in 10-run seventh inning\n| last = Echan\n| first = Michael via: MLB.com\n| date = August 30, 2006\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160313152207/http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060830&content_id=125814&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp\n| archive-date = March 13, 2016\n|access-date = April 5, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Volcanoes capped the '06 season by defeating the [[Boise Hawks]] three games to one, winning the NWL pennant on September 10. [[John Odom (baseball)|John Odom]] started 15 games for the Volcanoes.\n\n===2007 Season===\nThe Volcanoes broke their own record for wins in a season, finishing the season with a 57-19 mark, a .750 overall record; best in baseball that year. They won their second NWL championship in a row by defeating the [[Tri-City Dust Devils]] three games to one.  The team was honored with the Best Short-Season and Best Overall Team in the 2007 Minor League Baseball Awards.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | url = http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/awards/y2007/index.jsp\n  | title = 2007 MiLB.com Awards\n  | website = www.milb.com\n  | url-status = dead\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160420204917/http://www.milb.com/news/awards/y2007/index.jsp\n  | archive-date = April 20, 2016\n  | access-date = April 5, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\n===2008 Season===\nSalem-Keizer won the division pennant in 2008, but lost the championship series to the [[Spokane Indians]].\n\n===2009 Season===\nThe Volcanoes won the NWL title for the third time in 4 years, 3 games to 1 over the [[Tri-City Dust Devils]]. Their pitching staff recorded a phenomenal 0.69 ERA over the four-game set.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | last = Ghiroli via: MLB.com\n  | first = Brittany\n  | title = Volcanoes win Northwest crown ... again\n  | url = http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090911&content_id=6903062&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp\n  | website = www.milb.com\n  | date = September 10, 2009\n  | accessdate = April 5, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\n==Playoffs==\n*1998: Defeated [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 3-0 to win championship.\n*2001: Defeated [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2003: Lost to [[Spokane Indians|Spokane]] 3-0 in finals.\n*2006: Defeated [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2007: Defeated [[Tri-City Dust Devils|Tri-City]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2008: Lost to [[Spokane Indians|Spokane]] 3-1 in finals.\n*2009: Defeated [[Tri-City Dust Devils|Tri-City]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2013: Lost to [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 2-0 in semifinals.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Joe Biagini]], MLB Relief Pitcher\n*[[Hunter Bishop]], Minors Outfielder, first round draft pick\n*[[Emmanuel Burriss]], MLB/Minors Second Baseman\n*[[Brandon Crawford]], MLB Shortstop\n*[[Kevin Frandsen]], MLB Second Baseman\n*[[Conor Gillaspie]], MLB/Minors Third Baseman\n*[[Brian Horwitz]], MLB/Minors Outfielder\n*[[Travis Ishikawa]], MLB First Baseman\n*[[Tim Lincecum]], MLB Starting Pitcher\n*[[Joe Panik]], MLB Second Baseman\n*[[Buster Posey]], MLB Catcher\n*[[Ryan Vogelsong]], MLB Starting Pitcher\n*[[Pablo Sandoval]], MLB Third Baseman\n*[[Sergio Romo]], MLB Relief Pitcher\n*[[Dan Runzler]], MLB Relief Pitcher\n*[[Jonathan S\u00e1nchez]], MLB Starting Pitcher\n*[[Nate Schierholtz]], MLB Outfielder\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Roster==\n{{Salem-Keizer Volcanoes roster}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.volcanoesbaseball.com Salem-Keizer Volcanoes official website]\n\n{{San Francisco Giants}}\n{{Northwest League}}\n{{Oregon Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Salem-Keizer Volcanoes| ]]\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Keizer, Oregon]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Giants minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Salem, Oregon|Volcanoes]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Northwest League teams]]\n[[Category:Professional baseball teams in Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed section|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name            = Salem-Keizer Volcanoes \n|founded         = 1997 \n|city            = Keizer, Oregon \n|misc            =\n|logo            = SalemKeizerVolcanoesLogo.PNG\n|uniformlogo     = SalemKeizerVolcanoesCapLogo.PNG\n|class level     = Short-Season A (1997\u2013present)\n|past class level=\n|current league  = [[Northwest League]] (1997\u2013present)\n|conference      =\n|division        = Southern Division\n|past league     =\n|majorleague     = [[San Francisco Giants]] (1997\u2013present)\n|pastmajorleague =\n|nickname        = Salem-Keizer Volcanoes (1997\u2013present)\n|pastnames       =\n|mascot          = Crater (1997-present)\n|ballpark        = [[Volcanoes Stadium]] (1997\u2013present)\n|pastparks       =\n|leaguenum       = 5\n|leaguechamps    = {{hlist|1998|2001|2006|2007|2009}}\n|divnum          = 7\n|divisionchamps  = {{hlist|1998|2001|2003|2006|2007|2008|2009}}\n|owner           = Jerry Walker<ref>{{cite web |title=Salem-Keizer Volcanoes Staff Directory |url=https://www.milb.com/salem-keizer/about/staff-directory |website=MiLB.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|manager         = Lenn Sakata<ref>{{cite web |title=Salem-Keizer Volcanoes Roster |url=http://www.milb.com/roster/index.jsp?sid=t578 |website=MiLB.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|gm              =\n|colors= Gray, lava red, obsidian, burnt gold, white<BR/>{{color box|#536878}} {{color box|red}} {{color box|#000}} {{color box|#CC5500}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}}}\nThe '''Salem-Keizer Volcanoes''' are a [[minor league baseball]] team in [[Keizer, Oregon|Keizer]], [[Oregon]], [[United States]]. They are a Short-Season Class A team in the [[Northwest League]], and have been an affiliate of the [[San Francisco Giants]] since the Volcanoes' inception in 1997. They play their home games at [[Volcanoes Stadium]], which opened in 1997 and seats 4,252 fans.\n\n==Baseball in the Salem Area==\nThe Salem-Keizer area has been home to professional baseball since 1940, when the [[Salem Senators]]  (an homage to Salem's role as Oregon's capital) were formed as a member of the Western International League (WIL). When the WIL reformed into the current Northwest League (NWL) in 1955, the Senators were a charter member of the new circuit. The Salem franchise played as the Senators until 1960, when it became a Class A affiliate of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] and adopted the parent club's nickname. The Salem Dodgers continued to play until the 1965 season, after which   the franchise was dormant for 17 years.\n\nIn 1977, former [[Stockton Ports]] owner/manager [[Carl W. Thompson Sr.|Carl Thompson]] purchased the Salem franchise and put it back on the field as an NWL member and Dodgers farm club. The revived Senators played until after the 1981 season, when the [[California Angels]] became the team's parent club.\n\nThe '82 Angels captured the first NWL championship by a Salem-area franchise, and became the first NWL champion with a losing regular-season record, a distinction which lasted until 2005.\n\nThe Salem Angels shifted their major-league affiliation and nickname back to the Dodgers after the 1987 season. The Dodgers played in Salem for two seasons, with future major-league star [[Mike Piazza]] on the team's 1989 roster.\n\nIn 1990, owners moved the Salem Dodgers to [[Yakima, Washington]], mainly due to lack of adequate facilities. The Salem club had played its home games at the [[Chemeketa Community College]] field, which lacked a grandstand, permanent concession stands and other amenities. It would be seven years before pro baseball returned to the Salem-Keizer metropolitan area.\n\n==Reborn as the Volcanoes==\nIn 1996, [[Bellingham Mariners|Bellingham Giants]] co-owners Jerry Walker and William Tucker announced that they were moving the NWL franchise to [[Keizer, Oregon]], a city of 22,000 located immediately north of Salem. The Bellingham club, short-season Class A affiliate of the [[San Francisco Giants]], had the NWL's lowest attendance figures during each of its two seasons.  The move devastated Bellingham baseball fans, many of whom still harbor hard feelings for the entire Giants organization in general and the Volcanoes in particular.\n\nKeizer had striven to assert itself as an independent, thriving city for 12 years since the former Salem suburb had become an incorporated municipality. City officials, led by Mayor Dennis Koho, and civic leaders worked toward getting a new baseball stadium located and built in Keizer. The area had lacked a suitable facility for pro baseball since the early 1960s, when the Salem Dodgers vacated historic Waters Field (which burned down in 1966).\n\nVolcanoes Stadium was built in less than a year, on a tract of land adjacent to [[Interstate 5 in Oregon|Interstate 5]] just northwest of the Keizer interchange. The 4,252-seat facility was ready for the debut of the Salem-Keizer Volcanoes in 1997. Two years later, the American Institute of Architects honored the Volcanoes with a design award for the stadium.\n\nVolcanoes Stadium also hosts all five of [[Oregon Schools Activities Association|Oregon's state high school baseball]] championship games. In 1998, the [[University of Oregon]] [[1998 Oregon Ducks football team|football team]] played its spring Green-White game in the stadium in early May.<ref name=strshn>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3UxWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6usDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1908%2C1104766 |work=Eugene Register-Guard  |last=Clark |first=Bob |title=UO starters shine against the reserves |date=May 3, 1998 |page=1G}}</ref>\n\nArea fans chose the nickname \"Volcanoes\" in a contest. The new franchise was designated as a \"Salem-Keizer\" team, despite its location, in order to incorporate both the history and the prestige of the larger city and state capital.\n\nAs of 2009, the Volcanoes have won seven Western Division titles, including four straight between 2006 and 2009. The others came in the 1998, 2001 and 2003 seasons.\n\nSalem-Keizer has won five NWL championships, in 1998, 2001, 2006, 2007, and 2009.\n\nIn 2001, the Volcanoes won the Freitas Award as the best short-season Class A baseball franchise in the U.S.\n\nNotable former Salem-Keizer Volcanoes include [[Brian Horwitz]], [[Joe Nathan]], [[Ryan Vogelsong]], [[Pablo Sandoval]], [[Kurt Ainsworth]], [[Jesse Foppert]], [[Travis Ishikawa]], [[Noah Lowry]], [[Tim Lincecum]], [[Buster Posey]], and [[Lance Niekro]]. Since 1997, 84 former Volcanoes have played in the major leagues.\n\nTwo former Volcanoes also played in the inaugural [[2006 in baseball|2006]] [[World Baseball Classic]]: [[Joe Nathan]] (U.S.) and [[Jonathan S\u00e1nchez]] (Puerto Rico).\n\n===2006 Season===\n[[File:Volcanoes Stadium Keizer Oregon wide.JPG|thumb|Volcanoes Stadium]]\nThe Volcanoes celebrated their 10th season in Salem-Keizer by ending the regular season with an NWL-record 55 victories. (The record is for the years since the league adopted a 76-game regular season.) The Volcanoes led the NWL in many categories during 2006, and set franchise records of:\n\n* Most consecutive games won (12)\n* Most runs in an inning (10), in the seventh inning of a 19-3 rout of the [[Vancouver Canadians|Canadians]] on August 30. In that game, catcher Adam Witter hitting the team's first ever [[Hitting for the cycle|cycle]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.minorleaguebaseball.com/app/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060830&content_id=125814&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp\n| title = Volcanoes' Witter hits for cycle {{hyphen}} Catcher caps feat with homer in 10-run seventh inning\n| last = Echan\n| first = Michael via: MLB.com\n| date = August 30, 2006\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160313152207/http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060830&content_id=125814&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp\n| archive-date = March 13, 2016\n|access-date = April 5, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Volcanoes capped the '06 season by defeating the [[Boise Hawks]] three games to one, winning the NWL pennant on September 10. [[John Odom (baseball)|John Odom]] started 15 games for the Volcanoes.\n\n===2007 Season===\nThe Volcanoes broke their own record for wins in a season, finishing the season with a 57-19 mark, a .750 overall record; best in baseball that year. They won their second NWL championship in a row by defeating the [[Tri-City Dust Devils]] three games to one.  The team was honored with the Best Short-Season and Best Overall Team in the 2007 Minor League Baseball Awards.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | url = http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/awards/y2007/index.jsp\n  | title = 2007 MiLB.com Awards\n  | website = www.milb.com\n  | url-status = dead\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160420204917/http://www.milb.com/news/awards/y2007/index.jsp\n  | archive-date = April 20, 2016\n  | access-date = April 5, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\n===2008 Season===\nSalem-Keizer won the division pennant in 2008, but lost the championship series to the [[Spokane Indians]].\n\n===2009 Season===\nThe Volcanoes won the NWL title for the third time in 4 years, 3 games to 1 over the [[Tri-City Dust Devils]]. Their pitching staff recorded a phenomenal 0.69 ERA over the four-game set.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | last = Ghiroli via: MLB.com\n  | first = Brittany\n  | title = Volcanoes win Northwest crown ... again\n  | url = http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090911&content_id=6903062&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp\n  | website = www.milb.com\n  | date = September 10, 2009\n  | accessdate = April 5, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\n==Playoffs==\n*1998: Defeated [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 3-0 to win championship.\n*2001: Defeated [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2003: Lost to [[Spokane Indians|Spokane]] 3-0 in finals.\n*2006: Defeated [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2007: Defeated [[Tri-City Dust Devils|Tri-City]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2008: Lost to [[Spokane Indians|Spokane]] 3-1 in finals.\n*2009: Defeated [[Tri-City Dust Devils|Tri-City]] 3-1 to win championship.\n*2013: Lost to [[Boise Hawks|Boise]] 2-0 in semifinals.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Joe Biagini]], MLB Relief Pitcher\n*[[Hunter Bishop]], Minors Outfielder, first round draft pick\n*[[Emmanuel Burriss]], MLB/Minors Second Baseman\n*[[Brandon Crawford]], MLB Shortstop\n*[[Kevin Frandsen]], MLB Second Baseman\n*[[Conor Gillaspie]], MLB/Minors Third Baseman\n*[[Brian Horwitz]], MLB/Minors Outfielder\n*[[Travis Ishikawa]], MLB First Baseman\n*[[Tim Lincecum]], MLB Starting Pitcher\n*[[Joe Panik]], MLB Second Baseman\n*[[Buster Posey]], MLB Catcher\n*[[Ryan Vogelsong]], MLB Starting Pitcher\n*[[Pablo Sandoval]], MLB Third Baseman\n*[[Sergio Romo]], MLB Relief Pitcher\n*[[Dan Runzler]], MLB Relief Pitcher\n*[[Jonathan S\u00e1nchez]], MLB Starting Pitcher\n*[[Nate Schierholtz]], MLB Outfielder\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Roster==\n{{Salem-Keizer Volcanoes roster}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.volcanoesbaseball.com Salem-Keizer Volcanoes official website]\n\n{{San Francisco Giants}}\n{{Northwest League}}\n{{Oregon Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Salem-Keizer Volcanoes| ]]\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Keizer, Oregon]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Giants minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Salem, Oregon|Volcanoes]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Northwest League teams]]\n[[Category:Professional baseball teams in Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Daknalo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Wikilink Lenn Sakata in infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salem-Keizer_Volcanoes"}
